snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: If They Can't Breathe, None of Us Can
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter and we need to amplify their voices right now. We need to stand in solidarity because they are fighting for justice. They are fighting against police racism, violence and brutality that kills Black people. 

They are standing for the right to life - something we can all lose if we allow police to continue lethal racism. If Black people can't breathe, none of us can.  

Justice for George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Armbery, Eric Garner, Michael Brown Jr., Duane Christian, Andrew Loku, Jermaine Carby, D'Andre Campbell and the thousands of other precious lives lost.

Here is the Black Lives Matter website:
https://www.blacklivesmatter.com/

Recommended reading: Desmond Cole's "The Skin We're In: A Year of Black Resistance and Power" published by Double Day Canada:
https://amzn.to/3eynmYb

Here is my Warrior Life Podcast interview with Desmond Cole, journalist, best-selling author and social justice warrior advocating against anti-Black racism and violence by police and society:
https://www.soundcloud.com/pampalmater/desmond-cole-on-anti-black-racism-in-canada-us

Please also check out Robyn Maynard's "Policing Black Lives: State Violence in Canada: From Slavery to the Present" published by Fernwood Publishing:
https://amzn.to/3dkKlWn

Here is my Warrior Life Podcast interview with social justice warrior Robyn Maynard, Black feminist writer, activist and educator:
https://www.soundcloud.com/pampalmater/robyn-maynard-on-anti-black-racism-in-canada


Please note: Nothing in this podcast/video advocates for violence on Indigenous territories.

Please also note: The information contained in this podcast/video should not be misconstrued as legal, financial or medical advice, nor should it be relied on as such. This podcast represents fair political comment.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Black Out Tuesday - George Floyd - Malkom X speech Forgiven FATE
snippet.description:
To follow up the NEWS
https://blacklivesmatter.com/




Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international human rights movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protest turns violent in London
snippet.description:
(1 Jun 2020) Clashes erupted in central London on Sunday after a largely peaceful Black Lives Matter protest.
Tension escalated as police tried to clear a junction in Parliament Square blocked by protesters.
The demonstrators were rallying against the death of George Floyd, who died in Minnesota on May 25 after a police officer pressed his knee on his neck, which had a sparked a week of demonstrations in the US.
A number of people were seen being arrested and put into police vans, the Metropolitan Police Service said late Sunday 23 people had been arrested in relation to the protests.
One protester, who chose to remain nameless, said the demonstrators had been protesting peacefully and criticised the actions of the police.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER | children's books |
snippet.description:
Today, I share six children's books with you, that enforce the Black Lives Matter movement and educate children about race. These children's books spread the BLACK LIVES MATTER message and that racism should not be accepted. EVER. Children should learn from a young age to not discriminate against people because of the colour of their skin and it saddens me that racism and inequality is ever present in our society and all over the world. I hope that these books are used more and more in schools and in homes to show children that racism is of the past and should not exist in today's society. Something must be done. SOON!

I encourage parents, carers, teachers to use these books to open up discussions about race and racism with children.

Please educate yourself and others, read these books, read websites, make donations, sign petitions, speak up at protests. George Floyd didn't deserve what happened to him, no innocent man or woman deserves that, black lives matter.

Here's some useful links that you can use:
https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/#
^^tells you all the different things you can do

donate any spare money: https://blacklivesmatter.com
or
https://www.gofundme.com/f/georgefloyd\

sign: https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-...

there's so many available resources online so please do loads of research, thank you for watching.

LINKS TO THE BOOKS I SPOKE ABOUT!

My hair is beautiful by Shauntay Grant: https://amzn.to/2My9127
Sulwe by Lupita Nyong'o: https://amzn.to/2zewsui
Little leaders - Bold women in black history by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3760bSy
Dream big little one by Vashti Harrison: https://amzn.to/3cCIIT2
We march by Shane. W. Evans: https://amzn.to/375YVic
Race cars by Jenny Devenny: https://amzn.to/2Uj90mT
Something happened in our town by Ann Hazzard, Marianne Celano, and Marietta Collins: https://amzn.to/3dGez6A

Song I used (copyright free):

Intro song: Joakim Karud - By The Croft

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter OKC issues demands
snippet.description:
Rev. T. Sheri Dickerson, executive director of the Black Lives Matter OKC chapter, holds a press conference outside the city hall building in downtown Oklahoma City. Dickerson issued the group's following demands:

● An apology from Police Chief Wade Gourley and Mayor David Holt and the immediate resignation of Gourley, whose lack of leadership resulted in aggressive actions by the police towards peaceful protesters, escalating tensions and resulting in violence that could have been avoided.
● The immediate release without charges of all incarcerated protestors who were arrested for nonviolent offenses or “resisting arrest” while defending themselves or their loved ones from unlawful use of excessive force by OKC PD and the sheriff.
● Disciplinary action and termination be taken against all police officers who violently attacked peaceful protesters.
● The immediate installation of an independent citizens’ complaint review board for the OKC PD, which will have authority to review all complaints, including use of force, and discipline offending officers.
● Mayor Holt meet with us within 24 hours.
● Provision of training in de-escalation tactics for all OCPD officers, which must include training in interactions with persons who have mental health issues as well as training that includes cultural sensitivity.
● The immediate public release of the arrest record of Olain Jefferson, Jr. and body cam footage of all police involved in his arrest.
● The immediate public release of all video footage of the OKCPD incident involving and resulting in the death of Derrick Ollie Sr.
● The arrest and prosecution of David Stewart for the kidnapping and illegal confinement of Mr. Travis Miller Sr.
● Justice for the family of Mr. Elray Barber who was shot and killed by OKCPD on Christmas Eve 2019.
● Justice for Ms. Rolana Keeler who was shot by OKCPD on Christmas Eve 2019 while unarmed.
● Mayor Holt commit to the construction of a grocery store on the Eastside of OKC to be completed within 6 months.
● The granting of clemency and immediate release of wrongfully charged member of our community, Julius Jones, by Governor Stitt.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter. Let's work together as a community to make a real difference.

Not sure where to begin? There are so many ways to get involved. This movement is fluid and growing every day, so it is up to us to seek out spaces where we can make a difference. Look on social media for local fundraising efforts that speak to you. Amplify those efforts and continue spreading the word.

Below are some of our personal recommendations:

DONATE.

Split a donation between 40 Community Bail Funds, including the LGBTQ Fund.
https://secure.actblue.com/donate/bai...

Help fund nonprofit journalism covering criminal justice.
https://www.themarshallproject.org/do...

Donate to the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
https://www.naacpldf.org/

Since May 29, there have been over 125 press freedom violations reported by journalists during the demonstrations against the death of George Floyd.
https://cpj.org/

SPEAK OUT.

Sign Amnesty International’s Letter to Minnesota Governor Tim Walz.
https://www.amnesty.org/en/get-involv...

Make Calls with The Action Pac. Dial the number and it will walk you through the process and what to say.
https://www.justiceforbigfloyd.com/ma...

LEARN.

Watch the documentary 13th which covers the criminalization of African Americans and the U.S. prison boom.
https://www.netflix.com/title/80091741

Dive deeper. Take the Open Yale Course “African American History: From Emancipation to the Present.”
https://oyc.yale.edu/african-american...

***I have copied and pasted everything above from a channel called unus annus***
***I will be deleting any and all disrespectful comments***

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter to Me - a Jewish Response to Racial Injustice
snippet.description:
If you are Black, your life matters to me. Today I wanted to share a Jewish perspective on why the #BlackLivesMatter movement is so important to me and my thoughts on racism and injustice. The world we live in is fractured but it is our greatest responsibility to repair it.⁣ In the Torah we read, ⁣Tzedek tzedek tirdof⁣ תרדף צדק ‎צדק ⁣Justice, justice you shall pursue.⁣ As a #Jewish person, as a mother, as an American - your life matters to me.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter is how we end the divide and rule crisis of Covid-19 -- Untitled UK: 2 June (E17)
snippet.description:
Architectural journalist discusses how the death of George Floyd exposes the massive inqualities caused by divide and rule politics in the USA and elsewhere. 



This episode discusses how the Black Lives Matter campaign offers everyone an opportunity to work together to overthrow the dominance of divide and rule politics, and creater a fairer, safer and healthier society for everyone. 



It looks at new research by Public Health England showing how BAME people are much more at risk of death of Covid-19 than white people and discusses the likely impact of health inequalities on these findings. 



The show also looks at recent remarks by former UK prime minister Gordon Brown calling for a united global response to the crisis and a crackdown on the trillions of dollars of wealth hidden in tax havens. 

Thanks for watching and please share your comments!

snippet.title: Liverpool Black Lives Matter Protestors
snippet.description:
ID: 

A huge crowd at St George's Hall in Liverpool this evening in solidarity with the race protest movement in the US.

The wave of protests sweeping the UK is in support of the anger about violence suffered by black people at the hands of police in the US, a feeling galvanised by the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis earlier this month. 

Mr Floyd died after a police officer put his knee on the unarmed black man's neck for more than eight minutes despite him warning that he could not breathe.

snippet.title: Statue honouring slave trader Edward Colston is toppled at Black Lives Matter protest in Bristol
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A statue of Edward Colston, a 17th-century slave trader, has been toppled in Bristol by Black Lives Matter protesters.

Video footage shows the statue being pulled down using a rope.

After it falls during the protests on Sunday people can be seen dancing atop the statue and cheering.

It comes as thousands of protesters gather across the UK to march against racism following the death of George Floyd, a black man who died while in police custody in Minneapolis.

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/black-lives-matter-protest-george-floyd-a4462046.html

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter...
snippet.description:
R.I.P to everyone who battled with racism 

Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international activist movement, originating in the African-American community, that campaigns against violence and systemic racism towards black people. BLM regularly holds protests speaking out against police killings of black people, and broader issues such as racial profiling, police brutality, and racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system.

Police killed at least 104 unarmed black people in 2015, nearly twice each week. (See which police departments were responsible for these deaths)

Nearly 1 in 3 black people killed by police in 2015 were identified as unarmed, though the actual number is likely higher due to underreporting

36% of unarmed people killed by police were black in 2015 despite black people being only 13% of the U.S. population

Unarmed black people were killed at 5x the rate of unarmed whites in 2015

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter: People's Rebellion in the Belly of the Beast
snippet.description: Since Monday May 25 people have taken the streets in cities across the United States demanding justice for George Floyd who was killed by police in Minneapolis. A video of his unjust murder circulated widely across social media and his death has served as the tipping point for people frustrated with the racist, capitalist system. The protests are some of the most intense and largest seen since the 2014 Ferguson uprising which occurred after police murdered 18-year-old Michael Brown.

snippet.title: Black Lives and Voices Matter: an art exposition (fundraiser closed!)
snippet.description:
Hi everyone!
Once again I wanted to thank you all for the massive support on this project, and I’m so proud of all the good that you all have created just by watching. I hope you’ve found some new artists to enjoy and found a desire to always lend a helping hand where you can!

Recently, I spoke with a representative at YouTube about the video fundraiser and it was found to violate Google monetization guidelines, in that it encourages “users to click or watch ads to increase the contribution” and I am working with them to amend that so that the video can return and stay up!
However, because YouTube so believed in the essence of the project, they have committed to making a donation equal to what all of you have raised in the name of the project. I’m still looking at which organisations will get what, and the final donation amount, but to say a phrase i’ve gotten very used to saying this week, “I’ll let you know when I know!”

The video will still be up on my channel although you’ll notice there’s no more ads to watch, and the title and intro may be a little different, but I still want you all to be able to enjoy the supremely talented artists involved. Please check them out on all of their listed social media, for this project wouldn’t be possible without them!

I’d also like to thank all of the media outlets and creators using their platforms to give this project some shine. Your dedication to using your voice to share and do good work speaks volumes and I am entirely grateful. Perhaps more importantly, to all of you people who shared this video on your instagram, spoke about it with your friends and families, tweeted and watched and were excited at a way to help that you couldn’t otherwise, I am BEYOND proud of you, and thank you for being part of the power behind social change. 

Thank you so so much everyone!
As always, I’ll keep you posted!
Love, Zoe 💗

In addition to watching this video and listening to the great artists in it, here are some petitions to sign in relation to these tragic losses and other ways to help.

https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Vancouver Protest 2020 | Anti Racism Rally
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter 
Hundreds gathered outside the Vancouver Art Gallery Sunday afternoon for a protest demanding justice following George Floyd’s death at the hands of Minneapolis police this week.

This is the latest Vancouver Protest 2020 which shows Anti Racism Rally. 

Protesters wore masks to prevent coronavirus spread and brought signs bearing messages such as “Black lives matter,” “silence=compliance,” and “I can’t breathe,” the latter referencing Floyd’s last words as a police officer knelt on his neck for several minutes before he died. 

There was a moment of silence held at the demonstration to honour Floyd and other victims of police brutality before speeches and calls to action. Organizers plan to have the rally stay in Robson Square and not go on a march downtown, partly to avoid coronavirus spread and partly to avoid conflict with commuters and potential anti-protesters. 

The officer who held his knee to Floyd’s neck has now been charged with third degree murder and manslaughter. But Callendar-Prasad and other demonstrators want the other officers present at the time to be charged as well.

“This is the time to fight. This is the time to unite. No matter your skin colour, your pigment, where you’re from, this is something you should care about,” they said in an Instagram video preparing for the demonstration.

#BlackLivesMatter #BLM #VancouverProtest #GeorgeFloyd #AntiRacism #protest2020 #NVAliveDiaries

snippet.title: What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"? | Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
What's wrong with saying "all lives matter"?   ABC10 anchor Chris Thomas explains.
Follow Chris at https://www.facebook.com/ChrisThomasNews/

There have been protests, demonstrations, and riots over George Floyd's death for the past week. Well, that's the assumption, at least. In the 90s, 15-year-old Latasha Harlins was shot in the back of the head when she turned her back to a fight that broke out in a store. The Korean grocer who shot her was given a suspended sentence, probation, and a fine. Shortly after, the four officers that brutally beat Rodney King were found not guilty! 

These two events led to an explosion (the LA riots) of rage based on the recent examples that black lives don't matter. On February 23rd, 2020, Ahmaud Arbery was jogging when a pickup truck blocked his path. Two people were inside; one jumped out with a gun and shot Arbery. Oh, by the way, this was filmed by another participant in the attack. It was not until May 7th that the McMichaels were arrested. This arrest did not happen until public outrage spread across social media when the video was released on May 5th. Why the outrage? Well, the life of Ahmaud Arbery didn't matter enough to those in power to have the McMichaels arrested immediately for Arbery's death instead of waiting for more than two months. 

By now, you've all seen the video of the officer pressing his knee on the neck of George Floyd. If you watched the video, you heard him begging for the opportunity to breathe. A request that sounds sadly similar to Eric Garner. For over five minutes, officer Derek Chauvin and the other officers ignored Floyd's requests to breathe. 

These two events, like the two events in the 90s, have led to an explosion of outrage in the form of protests, demonstrations, and riots. Why? Because many Americans now understand why it is necessary to say, Black Lives Matter.

snippet.title: Overthink Podcast # 12 - K-Pop Army Helps Black Lives Matter Keep Trending
snippet.description:
While following the situation in the US with the George Floyd protests, I started to notice something. The K-POP Army was helping the BLM hashtags trend and keeping it trending. This plus other thoughts I had through out the day. a free thought podcast.

RECORDED ON FRIDAY MAY 29, 2020 
--
About the Overthink Podcast:
This podcast usually tackles tough topics with a few sprinklings of fun and silly ones thrown in the mix to keep things light. I am a storyteller so I like to lead you on a journey as to how I go from where I started to where I am now. Not only that but my thoughts on these topics come to me through my life experiences so I can't just say this is this and that is that without explaining the why behind it. 

I've tried teaching or using an instructional method to show the inforamtion that I'd gotten but it just doesn't interest me but I love stories so here we are. Some long winded stories with some lessons I've learned along the way through inside.
--
Please take time to subscribe and like if you found value in my video and not only that but also leave a comment and tell me what you thought!
.+SUBSCRIBE+.
.+LIKE+.
.+COMMENT+.
--
Connect with me on:
.+Twitter - https://twitter.com/elenaebaptiste
.+Website - https://letsoverthinkthis.com/

snippet.title: YES, SHOW SOLIDARITY WITH BLACK LIVES MATTER BUT ALSO INTEGRATE IT WITH THE CLASS STRUGGLE TOO
snippet.description:
As pointed out by the Black Panther Party "We don't care what anybody says. We don't think to fight fire with fire. We think to fight fire with water. We're going to fight racism, not with racism but we're going to fight it with solidarity. We say we're not going to fight Capitalism with Black Capitalism, but we're going to fight it with Socialism." 

Identity politics in itself is a very complicated subject when it comes to Marxist-Leninist theory because while there are a lot of differences between identity politics and class politics, there are also a lot of overlaps too.

--- SOME GOOD RESOURCES ---

America Never Stood For Freedom - Hakim: https://youtu.be/-HflHrHvYsw 

US: What Is To Be Done? - Hakim: https://youtu.be/f68HZ0hEqeY 

New Communist Parties Ditching Identity Politics - Jason Unruhe: https://youtu.be/kSmfrH8hjLw 

Yes, Identity Politics Divides The Left - Jason Unruhe: https://youtu.be/iEZcBbdgMU8 

Some Thoughts On Identity Politics - TheFinnishBolshevik: https://youtu.be/G9PyFR3Dr8I

Massive Protests Over George Floyd Murder (We Must Help!) - TheFinnishBolshevik: https://youtu.be/8sTYEz6HigM

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters smash window of CHP cruisers near downtown LA I ABC7
snippet.description:
Hundreds of people marched through downtown Los Angeles Wednesday in a Black Lives Matter protest over the death of George Floyd in Minnesota. The march resulted in a violent confrontation with police and the shutting down of the 101 Freeway.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Modesto March
snippet.description:
More than 1,000  protesters marched through the streets of Modesto for more than seven miles on May 31, 2020 to protest the death of George Floyd and police brutality throughout the nation. After hours of peaceful protest, the march was marred with violence when agitators clashed with police along J Street.

Filmed and Edited: Frankie Tovar
#ModestoProtest #GeorgeFloyd #BLMProtesters

snippet.title: Freedom; where are you? #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
[1080p + headphones] 

➾ Legenda em português disponível.

"𝐼𝑡 𝑖𝑠 𝑖𝑚𝑝𝑜𝑠𝑠𝑖𝑏𝑙𝑒 𝑡𝑜 𝑏𝑒 𝑢𝑛𝑎𝑟𝑚𝑒𝑑 𝑤ℎ𝑒𝑛 𝑦𝑜𝑢𝑟 𝑏𝑙𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑛𝑒𝑠𝑠 𝑖𝑠 𝑡ℎ𝑒 𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑝𝑜𝑛 𝑡ℎ𝑒𝑦 𝑓𝑒𝑎𝑟."  ✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

Warning: this description will be very emotional, sorry for that.

A few years ago my mother decided to have a conversation with me, a conversation that I forced myself to never forget. I must have been 7 or 8 years old, and I remember I came home crying, because some boys had teased me in school. Then she told me that I shouldn't let myself be overwhelmed by certain people who had the wrong knowledge. That I should be proud of being black, proud of our origins. 
The years started to pass and I heard a lot of people saying that "this kind of thing did not exist in my country" (Brazil), that there is no racism here and I really wanted to believe that this is true. But the past few weeks have been difficult to take.
We are dying, we are being left there. NO MORE!
If you can, take a moment to make donations, or even to sign petitions.
THIS IS THE TIME FOR CHANGE, SAY NEVER AGAIN!

♦ Here you can find more informations: https://twitter.com/kiesdaya/status/1265782360252887040

JUSTICE FOR GEORGE FLOYD!
JUSTICE FOR JOÃO PEDRO!
JUSTICE FOR ALL WHO HAVE BEEN LOSING THEIR LIVES FOR YEARS ONLY FOR THE COLOR OF YOUR SKIN!
✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿

☂ INFO:

▽ Fandom: The Hate U Give
▽ Song: in the end;
▽ Coloring: Jula Misiak

☂ 

Where to find me: 
TWITTER[me, speaking a lot in Portuguese!]: @/lgtwoods
INSTAGRAM: @/rainbowofdust 

#fanvidfeed #BLACKLIVESMATTER #VIDASPRETASIMPORTAM

snippet.title: Never Enough - The Greatest Showman | black lives matter remix
snippet.description:
This week for #musicmonday is for the culture. Too many of us are dying unjustly. We need to pray. We need to donate. We need to buy black. We need to support people in office that want to bring justice. We need to stand together. This was the only way I could think to express how I feel about recent events. No more silence. It’s time for action #blm #blacklivesmatter #greatestshowman #parody #remix

Lyrics 

I can no longer hold my breath
Can’t let it stay this way
Injustice needs to end
MLK said, “Dream with me”
But racism is louder now
Can you feel it echoing?
Raise your hand
Will you stand here with me?
Don’t wanna do this without you

Coverage of a thousand protests
And a hashtag that gets you noticed
Will never be enough
Never be enough
Four police fired is still too little
These hands are sick and tired and it’ll
Never be enough 
Never be enough

Til we’re free
Never, never
Never, never
Never, I just want
To be free
Never enough
Never enough
Never enough
Please don’t 
Kill me
I can’t breath 

Unarmed kings and queens are dying
As soon as we wake up we’re fighting
This trauma is too much
But still to hope I clutch 
Allies speak up but it’s still too little 
I raise my hands and kneel but it’ll
Never be enough
When will we be enough 

To be free
Give them pressure
Show displeasure
Let me be free, can’t you see
Is this enough 
We try to be tough
But we just want
To be free
Can’t you see
Don’t kill me
I can’t breath

snippet.title: Does "Black Lives Matter" have 501(c)(3) nonprofit status?
snippet.description:
Authenticating Nonprofits

During times of crisis, it is imperative to authenticate the 501(c)(3) status of nonprofit organizations BEFORE you make financial contributions. 

Unfortunately, there are organizations that prey on the emotions of people who simply want to provide support to further their mission.  This video teaches you the steps I used to AUTHENTICATE the nonprofit status of "Black Lives Matter."

Note: This video is not professionally edited. I wanted to share the information quickly which did not allow the time required for editing.

snippet.title: Moving Protest Art: #JUSTICEFORGEORGE #BLACKLIVESMATTER
snippet.description:
George Floyd was murdered on May 25th 2020 by a Police Officer named Derek Chauvin. Chauvin knelt on Floyd's neck for 7 minutes despite Floyd begging with him saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "I'm about to die."

This tragedy has sparked protests and riots for #BlackLivesMatter not only in the US but now across the globe as people stand up against police brutality and institutionalised racism.

To those who criticise the #BlackLivesMatter movement: 
#Equality is a cause everyone should fight for. 
Whether it be through protests, fundraising, donations, petitions, music, art or film, we must do what we can to make people hear and make people see. No Justice, No Peace.

This artwork is the least I can do to continue to spread the message that we will not stand for inequality any longer, that we refuse to see human beings suffer.

"I understand that I will never be able to understand completely. But I stand with you and I will not let you do this alone. You were never meant to."

Thank you to the wonderful Dan Pacini for allowing me to use his new song, 'The Ballad of George Floyd' in this video. Dan is a good friend, a talented musician and dedicated activist and you can find more music from him and his band here: 
https://soundcloud.com/the-hypothetics 
https://instagram.com/danncheesemusic?igshid=1ed62iwww10a3

If you would like to see more of my work please subscribe to my YouTube Channel and check out my social media links:
Facebook (Art and Photography): https://www.facebook.com/RhiannonDavisVisualArt/
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/_rhiannondavis.visualart/
Twitter: https://twitter.com/_rhiannondavis

#BlackLivesMatter #JusticeForGeorge #Activism

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER - Spoken Word by Jordan Green
snippet.description:
black lives matter (too)

Every time I drive past a cop car
My body tenses up;
Much in the same way that
An old white lady might tense up
When she passes by me at night
Much like the old white lady,
I fear that I might lose my life
Even if I do everything right
-
You see, in this new world
Where compliance is defiance
In this new world
Where surviving a traffic stop is a science
In this new world
Where police are quick to resort to violence
In this new world
We refuse to be silenced
It’s time for a revolution; 
We demand the evolution
Of our justice system
-
How is it that the very ones that are here to
“Serve and protect” our communities
Live lives of impunity and immunity
To the same laws which they enforce
Through the use of deadly force?
Of course, they systematically endorse
These crimes against humanity
I mean, just look at “Blue Lives Matter”
A product of insanity
A protest to a protest
They project their vanity
They hear us, but they don’t listen
In one ear and out the other
“Vigilantes” undercover
Kill our sisters and our brothers
-
We must demand change
The people have the power
This world can be strange
And oftentimes sour
But we can prevent this
There’s strength in numbers
It’s time we wake up 
From our lifelong slumbers
We must come together
And unite as a nation
Strive to do better
And avoid the temptation
To destroy our own cities
Stop all the looting
You’re only polluting
The very places you wish to improve
It’s time we start making real power moves
Tear gas couldn’t make us cry
As much as the families 
Of those murdered at the hands 
Of the police
I wholeheartedly send 
My condolences to all the families
Of the deceased

snippet.title: STOP KILLING US | Enough is Enough | Black Lives Matter | iAMNisi
snippet.description:
Welcome to my VERY 1st Youtube Channel. My name is Nisi and I started this channel at first as a constructive coping mechanism while dealing with a very hectic life as a single mom. I started finding my voice on Instagram through my Blessing Lessons every morning on my InstaStory. 

Now I am taking it a bit step further by starting this channel. That way all of my Bossy Beauties & Beaus can all have one place to love, support, and encourage each other.

I N  T H I S  V I D E O
It was very difficult for me to make this video. I'm raising a Black Man and the nightmares we have for our sons are horrible and frightening and, unfortunately, reality. 

We cannot keep quiet any longer.
We will not be silent.
We will not stop
...until you do.

snippet.title: Raleigh Black Lives Matter Protest 5/31
snippet.description:
A montage of the Raleigh protest.

The last scene is the riot officers starting to march in. There were a 5 men trying to take over the protest and start a riot. One of them told me he wasn't even there for the protest, just to mess with people. The other 4 had baseball bats, they were escorted away from the protest, and they made their way back when the police came with tear gas

You have to separate the two. There are angry people being manipulated into becoming rioters. Their anger is justified. But we can't ignore the opportunists. They must be stopped

snippet.title: John Boyega makes impassioned speech at Black Lives Matter protest in London
snippet.description:
John Boyega has issued an emotional rallying cry in support of Black Lives Matter in London's Hyde Park. 'I need you to understand how painful it is to be reminded every day that your race means nothing,' the Star Wars actor said. 'Black lives have always mattered.' Boyega's speech was widely shared on social media after video was posted by SB.TV and others

snippet.title: The History of the #BlackLivesMatter Movement What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? BLM Explained
snippet.description:
The History Behind the #BlackLivesMatter Movement | What is the Black Lives Matter Movement? | BLM - This is a special video summarizing the events that have led to the creation and influence of the #blacklivesmatter movement. It covers how the #BlackLivesMatter BLM movement got started, and who started it. It lists the goals and problems that are being faced by the BLM. It lists several dozen names of people who have been killed by racial injustice and police brutality. It covers different protests around the United States of America, including involvements from athletes within the NBA and the NFL. Lastly, it mentions the most recent events of George Floyd's death in Minneapolis, Minnesota and the recent call for the acknowledgement and accountability of the police and the affirmation of the prosperity of black lives.

#BlackLivesMatter #GeorgeFloyd #BlackLifeMatters
tags: The History behind the BlackLivesMatter Movement

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - are the stats accurate? | Professor Wilfred Reilly
snippet.description:
The US (as well as large parts of the western world) has been gripped by protests in the wake of the appalling killing of George Floyd by american police. The black lives matter movement is central to the protests, but are the claims it makes accurate? I spoke to author and academic Wilfred Reilly about this. His argument is that the majority of the black lives matter movement's central assertions are inaccurate or misleading.

I understand that this is a highly contentious and emotive topic so please feel free to leave a comment letting us know if your thoughts (but try to keep them civil if possible).

Please give the video a LIKE AND SUBSCRIBE, thanks! Also remember to LEAVE US A COMMENT letting us know what you think.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest: This Is Tulsa: Part II
snippet.description:
#BlackLivesMatter #Tulsa #Protest

Do you know what makes Tulsa such an amazing city? It's the people who live here. To have such an outspoken and diverse community of citizens who want the best for their city and ALL the people who live here, and are willing to be active and vocal about those desires through peaceful protest.

Part of the reason it's important to document what's happening at these protests is to reinforce the fact that these are peaceful protests and not to let the narrative get co-opted by those who would use the opportunity for their own agendas.

snippet.title: POV Photography during Black Lives Matter protests in Stockholm City #blacklifematter #pov
snippet.description: Wazup guys! The black life matter movement is active even in Sweden and there are several ways people been protesting. Today we are in the middle of downtown in an area called Sergelstorg. The Black Life Matter had a huge manifestation going on and I took the time to really catch some of the people that demonstrated. Let me be clear that this idea of being in a crowdy place during the Covid 19 is not that clever and I wouldnt recommend any one. At the same time I am very happy to see sow many people demonstrate and really taking a stand for the unjustice that been going on. The event in Sergelstorg was very calm and people where acting accordingly. At least of what I saw :)

snippet.title: LIVE: Black Lives Matter-demonstratie in Den Haag
snippet.description:
In Den Haag zijn honderden mensen samengekomen om te demonstreren tegen racisme en politiegeweld. De deelnemers van de Black Lives Matter-demonstratie dragen mondkapjes en houden afstand van elkaar. 

NOS-verslaggever Hasan Coşkun vroeg ze waarom zij het belangrijk vinden om op het Malieveld te staan. Ook vraagt hij hoe zij hebben gekeken naar het protest op de Dam, waar geen afstand werd gehouden.

#blacklivesmatter #demonstratie #nos

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Boston Gay Men's Chorus
snippet.description:
Over the last 50 years, artists have turned to John Lennon and Yoko Ono’s “Imagine” in times of tragedy. One of the most moving renditions of the song was performed on November 14, 2015, the morning after a series of terrorist attacks at multiple locations in Paris killed 130 people. Pianist Davide Martello, playing on a piano stained with blood outside of the Le Bataclan theater where 90 people had been killed the night before, performed “Imagine” to a crowd of weeping mourners. 
 
The delicate ballad, written in 1971 as an anti-war anthem, remains as much a hymn to political protest today as it was five decades ago. In the days following the 9/11 terrorist attacks “Imagine” was put on Clear Channel’s “do not play” list because it was seen as too subversive. Even so, sales of the song soared and artists ranging from Neil Young to Tori Amos performed it in high profile settings to comfort survivors and a grieving nation.  
 
Last June, we performed “Imagine” as the penultimate song at our Pride concert. The version we sang was arranged by Mari Esabel Valverde, one of the few out transgender composers working in the industry today. We chose her arrangement because it plays with rhythm in deeply personal ways, making it possible for a 200+-member chorus to convey intimacy while singing in unison. This can be heard throughout the song, but most movingly near the end with the line, “And the world will live as one.”
 
We offer this video of our performance of “Imagine” from last June in homage to Black people of all genders who have lost their lives to police violence. The artwork included is from “Last Words,” a series of images depicting the last words of 11 victims of police violence created by Shirin Barghi, an Iranian multimedia journalist and filmmaker, who made them in response to police riots in Ferguson, Missouri in 2014.
 
“Seeing the way the authorities here used terms like ‘rioters’ and ‘looters’ to dismiss and trivialize overwhelmingly non-violent demonstrations in Ferguson was painful,” Barghi said at the time. “It brought back vivid memories of similar tactics used by Iranian officials against protestors in 2009.”
 
Photographic images and footage included in the video are largely from anti-violence, Black Lives Matters protests that have taken place in the Greater Boston area in the first week of June, 2020.

Watch Rabbi Reuven Wolf Live @ Maayon Yisroel!
—
Thank you for watching this video. I hope that you keep up with the daily videos I post on the channel, subscribe, and share your learnings with those that need to hear it. Your comments are always welcome, so please take a second and say ‘Hi’  ;)

—

►Check out our Website here: 
http://maayonyisroel.com/

—
#RabbiReuvenWolf
Rabbi Reuven Wolf is a world renowned educator and lecturer who has devoted his life to reaching out and rekindling the spirit of Judaism in his fellow Jews. Recognized as an inspiring and thought provoking lecturer, he has cultivated a unique talent to communicate deep and complex mystical ideas in a manner that is both compelling and applicable to the greater public, and his lessons are charged with an enthusiasm and vigor that impacts listeners both intellectually and emotionally. Rabbi Wolf was raised in the Ropshetz Chassidic dynasty, educated in the Belz and Bluzhev Yeshivos, and later, in the famous Lithuanian schools of Slabodkea and Mir. He is profoundly influenced by Jewish Mysticism and Kabbalah, and particularly Chabad Chassidic philosophy.

Since 1995, Rabbi Wolf has been teaching students of all ages, from elementary school children to adults, and has lectured across North America. #MaayonYisroel was founded in 2006 by Rabbi Wolf and Haki Abhesera, as a center to fulfill the vision of spreading the profound mystical teachings of #Chassidus

The name "Maayon Yisroel," which means "wellsprings of Israel," is indicative of our mission to enrich and inspire the Jewish people with the deep, mystical teachings of the Baal Shem Tov and other Chassidic masters.

Rabbi Yisroel Baal Shem Tov, a 16th century Jewish mystic, was renowned for his unconditional love for the Jewish People, who worked to bring together Jews of all types to be inspired and nurtured in their appreciation of and relationship with G-d.

Through principles derived from his teachings, we aim to follow in the noble tradition of rejuvenating Yiddishkeit by showing how mystical ideas can be applied to modern life. These concepts which until now, have been largely inaccessible to the English-speaking public, have the power to provide the spirituality that Jews today complain is so often lacking in their experience of Judaism, as a mechanical and technical series of laws.

http://www.maayon.com/spotify

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: COMO OS FAMOSOS ESTÃO CONTRIBUINDO?
snippet.description:
Se não bastasse a pandemia que estamos encarando, o mundo parou para, mais uma vez, levantar a bandeira do Black Lives Matter. O movimento, que no Brasil ficou conhecido como Vidas Pretas Importam, tomou conta das notícias nos últimos dias por causa da morte do ex-segurança George Floyd, que foi imobilizado por um policial branco com o joelho, em Minneapolis, nos Estados Unidos. Além disso, aqui no Brasil, tivemos o caso do João Pedro, adolescente de 14 anos que foi assassinado com um tiro nas costas no Complexo do Salgueiro, em São Gonçalo, no Rio de Janeiro. 

Diante dos casos recentes, o movimento Black Live Matter, que começou na época do governo Obama, em 2013, tomou proporções gigantescas e dominou as ruas e as redes sociais. Com tamanha repercussão, grandes celebridades estão usando sua influência e sua voz para poder protestar diante tamanha indignação.

Ariana Grande foi uma das artistas que foram às ruas.  A cantora saiu nas ruas de Minnesota, nos Estados Unidos, para fazer sua parte. Com um cartaz escrito Black Lives Mattter, ela caminhou junto com outros protestantes.

Quem também saiu de casa para protestar, foi a cantora Helsey. Junto com o namorado, Yungblud, ela chegou a postar alguns stories em seu Instagram, mostrando sua participação.

Sempre presente nas redes sociais, Viola Davis fez questão de publicar e divulgar uma petição que está recolhendo assinaturas, chamada Justice João Pedro e que tem como objetivo recolher 1.500.000 assinaturas e pressionar o governo do Rio de Janeiro. Além da atriz, a cantora Janelle Monáe também usou o Twitter para divulgar o abaixo assinado de João.

Katy Perry e Harry Styles decidiram ajudar de outra forma. Os cantores resolveram fazer doações para os fundos que pagam as fianças dos manifestantes que acabam sendo presos. No Twitter, Harry deixou claro que agora não basta não ser racista, é preciso ser anti racista. Além disso, anunciou em outro post que estava realizando a doação.

Beyoncé gravou um vídeo no Instagram, pedindo justiça par George Floyd, divulgando a petição que fizeram para o ex-segurança e afirmando que essa é uma luta de todos contra a brutalidade que está acontecendo.

#famosos #ofuxico #blacklivesmatter

localized.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER: COMO OS FAMOSOS ESTÃO CONTRIBUINDO?
localized.description:
Se não bastasse a pandemia que estamos encarando, o mundo parou para, mais uma vez, levantar a bandeira do Black Lives Matter. O movimento, que no Brasil ficou conhecido como Vidas Pretas Importam, tomou conta das notícias nos últimos dias por causa da morte do ex-segurança George Floyd, que foi imobilizado por um policial branco com o joelho, em Minneapolis, nos Estados Unidos. Além disso, aqui no Brasil, tivemos o caso do João Pedro, adolescente de 14 anos que foi assassinado com um tiro nas costas no Complexo do Salgueiro, em São Gonçalo, no Rio de Janeiro. 

Diante dos casos recentes, o movimento Black Live Matter, que começou na época do governo Obama, em 2013, tomou proporções gigantescas e dominou as ruas e as redes sociais. Com tamanha repercussão, grandes celebridades estão usando sua influência e sua voz para poder protestar diante tamanha indignação.

Ariana Grande foi uma das artistas que foram às ruas.  A cantora saiu nas ruas de Minnesota, nos Estados Unidos, para fazer sua parte. Com um cartaz escrito Black Lives Mattter, ela caminhou junto com outros protestantes.

Quem também saiu de casa para protestar, foi a cantora Helsey. Junto com o namorado, Yungblud, ela chegou a postar alguns stories em seu Instagram, mostrando sua participação.

Sempre presente nas redes sociais, Viola Davis fez questão de publicar e divulgar uma petição que está recolhendo assinaturas, chamada Justice João Pedro e que tem como objetivo recolher 1.500.000 assinaturas e pressionar o governo do Rio de Janeiro. Além da atriz, a cantora Janelle Monáe também usou o Twitter para divulgar o abaixo assinado de João.

Katy Perry e Harry Styles decidiram ajudar de outra forma. Os cantores resolveram fazer doações para os fundos que pagam as fianças dos manifestantes que acabam sendo presos. No Twitter, Harry deixou claro que agora não basta não ser racista, é preciso ser anti racista. Além disso, anunciou em outro post que estava realizando a doação.

Beyoncé gravou um vídeo no Instagram, pedindo justiça par George Floyd, divulgando a petição que fizeram para o ex-segurança e afirmando que essa é uma luta de todos contra a brutalidade que está acontecendo.

#famosos #ofuxico #blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: London Black Lives Matter protest over justice for George Floyd
snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters fill London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more

snippet.title: Australian journalists attacked live on air during Black Lives Matter protests in London
snippet.description:
Two Australian journalists have been set upon while reporting on Black Lives Matter protests in London. 

Nine News correspondent Ben Avery was crossing to the Today show this morning when he was ambushed by demonstrators and forced to abandon his live coverage. 

It comes after Nine's Europe Correspondent Sophie Walsh was attacked live on air while previewing a Black Lives Matter protest last night. 

Ms Walsh was live on the evening news in Adelaide when a man allegedly said Allahu Akbar before grabbing her. 
Her cameraman managed to chase down the attacker and hold him until police arrived.

He was allegedly found in possession of a screwdriver and arrested for threats to kill and carrying a weapon.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Hello,
I am really sad about what is happening in the world right now, what happened to George Floyd is truly disgusting and it wasn't the first time, things like this shouldn't been happening.
I wanted to make this video to raise awareness about the situation, things really need to change, we are all humans and we all need to be treated equally and with respect. 
I also thought it was important to include the scene where the police officer joins the protestants because I have seen many hate against police officers and a lot of unnecessary violence, please don't get confused on who the enemy is, don't hurt innocent people's properties and remember an eye for an eye makes the whole world blind.
If you want to help please do it fairly.
Thank you for watching and remember to be kind to others.

Jureth x

snippet.title: Black lives matter - a song
snippet.description:
This is for George Floyd and for the oppressed. He died for what? For being black. Black lives matter. Share the song for the sake of justice and for the sake of bringing down racism. No one deserves to die because they are born the way they are. No one deserves to be treated like black people/POC. BLACK LIVES MATTER. 

Thank you so much to all my friends who were willing to submit/did submit a video. Thank you. 

Ukulele chords used: Em, G, D, A

Lyrics:
It’s real, it always has been 
They matter but you chose to ignore them 
They feel their existence is a sin 
They’re dying at your hands 
Their blood is on your hands 

I can’t breathe, I can’t breathe 
George Floyd he pleaded 
May his soul rest in peace 
Because for him, his race we’re fighting 
Do you know how it feels? 
To feel unimportant 
How can you be so ignorant? 
To a man dying 
Did you think he was lying? 

My friends I know they’re scared 
This is the reality they live in 
Oh lord hear their prayers 
Save them from the privileged 
They are innocent
They were innocent 
Now they’re no longer on this earth 

Because they jogged
They walked 
They talked 
Because they shopped
They played games 
They said their prayers 
Because they drove 
Owned a phone 
Or asked a question 
Because they left a party 
Listened to loud music 
They were living happily 
You killed them
Because they sleep
Because they BREATHE 
Because they lived 

It’s real, it always has been 
They matter but you chose to ignore them 
They feel their existence is a sin 
They’re dying at your hands 
Their blood is on your hands

When you’re not the centre of attention

He’s not alone when it comes to oppression 

He deserves justice 
Damn right all of them do 
Black lives matter 
Shout it louder 

Because they’re tired of being minors 
Shout it louder for the people of colour 
Black lives matter 
Black lives matter

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! #JusticeForGeorgeFloyd #JusticeForTina #JusticeForUwa | Coffee Table Gist
snippet.description:
Wake Up Nigeria, June 1, 2020

On the coffee Table gist, Yomi Owope and Tope Olowoniyan spoke about the outrage going on in the world. The recent killing of a black man, #GeorgeFlyod in Minneapolis, US has led to mass protest across the country. Now, the killing of young girls in Nigeria? What's actually going on? 💔

Uwaila Omozuwa was just 22-years-old and a first year student of University Of Benin.What did she or her parents do wrong?
Tina was just 16-years-old and was innocent, but was hit by a bullet on Tuesday 26th May, when a police officer shot to disperse a crowd that had gathered after he opened fire on a bus driver who broke curfew rules.
Jennifer was another 12-year-old raped by 11 men.

snippet.title: Justice for George Floyd ‘Black lives matter’ ✊🏾
snippet.description:
Published on June 1,2020


Following the recent killing of George Floyd, many persons have been protesting across different state in the United States...video footage clearly shows Floyd being cuffed faced down and was kneeled on by 3 police officers one of whom was seeing kneeling in his neck... Floyd could be heard crying out “I can’t breathe” to which the officers showed no remorse...we stand with our black brothers and sister in this march for justice for Floyd and all the other black lives that was brutally taken away... “I can’t breathe”....black lives matter!!!

snippet.title: Washington D.C. Mayor Renames Street Near White House 'Black Lives Matter Plaza'
snippet.description:
Mayor of Washington DC Muriel Bowser says people around the country want their voices "heard" and "there are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized."

Bowser comments came Friday in explaining to reporters why city workers and volunteers painted the words Black Lives Matter in enormous bright yellow letters on the street leading to the White House.

"We know what's going... on in our country. There's a lot of anger, there's a lot of distrust of police in the government. There are people who are craving to be heard and to be seen and to have their humanity recognized. And we had the opportunity to send that message loud and clear on a very important street in our city."

"That message is to the American people that black lives matter, black humanity matters," said Bowser.

"And we as a city raise that up as part of our values as a city."

The street-painting project follows Bower’s verbal clashes with the Trump administration over the response to protests of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis.

Bowser has complained about the heavy-handed federal response and called for the removal of out-of-state National Guard troops.

She says their differences highlight the need for D.C. to be a state and have more control over its internal affairs.

While not addressing the painted mural, President Trump continued his attacks on Bowser in tweets Friday.

“The incompetent Mayor of Washington, D.C., MayorBowser, who's budget is totally out of control and is constantly coming back to us for ‘handouts,' is now fighting with the National Guard, who saved her from great embarrassment over the last number of nights," he tweeted. "If she doesn't treat these men and women well, then we'll bring in a different group of men and women!”

The mayor fired back "that we all have to just refocus on on what's in front of us."

"Our nation is hurting. It's in need of healing and leadership at all levels, all the way from the top to mayors like me and to all of us to focus on how we bring people together."

The city's police chief Peter Newsham also talked about the continued protests and they "anticipate numbers that are larger than any of the numbers that we've seen to this point," on Saturday.

"The critical thing for us and ensuring that the city is safe when we have large gatherings outside of the public health issues is to ensure that we don't have people who are going to be inclined to be involved in bad behavior. So that's more of our focus than the actual numbers."

snippet.title: George Floyd's death sparks #BlackLivesMatter protests across America
snippet.description:
You might have heard that there are big protests going on in America right now, and many have turned violent. They started after an unarmed black man arrested by police was killed. His name was George Floyd. A 46-year-old man who died while being restrained by a police officer.

The incident made a lot of people really angry. Many have accused police of treating black people unfairly compared to how they treat white people, something they say has been happening for a long, long time. Protests first began in the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd died, but they've now spread across the country including in New York City, LA and in Washington. While a lot of them started as peaceful, many have turned violent. Cars have been set on fire, shops looted and buildings vandalised.

While the Government says it understands people's frustration, they say violence is not the answer. The protests haven't stopped, and lots of people, including some powerful and well-known ones, say they want to see change. 
 
KYLIE JENNER BILLIONAIRE BLUFF
Kylie Jenner isn't actually a billionaire, at least according to business magazine Forbes. Forbes called her the world's youngest billionaire in March of last year, thanks to her enormous cosmetic company. But now, Forbes says it was misled about how much her brand actually makes, and Kylie's not happy about it.
 
SPACEX DOCKS
In news that's well and truly out of this world, a SpaceX craft carrying two NASA astronauts has docked at the International Space Station. It's the first manned space flight from the US in nearly 10 years. The Crew Dragon capsule, carrying astronauts Bob Benkhen and Doug Hurley, finally blasted into space over the weekend, after the first launch was called off due to bad weather. Everything went swimmingly, the Falcon 9 rocket separated as planned, a few minutes into their trip, and the capsule carried on its 19 hour journey toward the international space station.

As is tradition, they gave the Crew Dragon a nickname: Endeavour. And to show off Endeavour's abilities, the capsule docked automatically to the international space station. We don't know how long they'll stay on board before returning home, but it could be as long as four months. SpaceX is hoping the Endeavour 's success is a sign of things to come, with more flights to and from the ISS set for later this year.
 
TAKING THE REIGNS
Getting off to a royally strong start, the Queen herself, on a horse. She's been living at Windsor Castle in lockdown with her husband, Prince Philip, but she's clearly happy to get back in the saddle. A lot more people will be, too. From today, horse racing will be the first major sport allowed again in the UK, after an 11-week shutdown.
 
THE EAGLE HAS LANDED
It's hard to imagine a more exciting ride than being on the back of a wedge-tailed eagle. Unfortunately, that means being a small, solar-powered GPS tracker. Scientists have attached the devices to study the birds' flight paths in Tasmania, with their locations updated every six seconds. One bird managed to travel nearly 250 kilometres around the state in eight hours.
 
CAMEL LONG FOR THE RIDE
The race to end all races: The Uluru Camel Cup. Where competitors can face off by throwing camel poo. And follow it up by climbing on a camel? For the first time, the Camel Cup was run without crowds because of COVID-19 restrictions. But the race was as tense as ever.

__________________________________________

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - police brutality | spoken word poetry
snippet.description:
The needless and brutal murder of #GeorgeFloyd is yet another reminder of our broken system of systemic racism, police brutality and the criminalisation of blackness, across society. When man helplessly says #icantbreathe and is ignored by the very people here to 'serve and protect' this is why there is the need for a Black Lives Matter movement. 
In dedication to him, and the injustice he faced, this spoken word poetry is written about the deeply harmful police brutality and senseless killing, which needs to be addressed! 
Peace and love to the family of George Floyd🖤 #BlackLivesMatter

Another life lost in America...
so maybe there could be a race problem in the united states after i’ve lost count of the deaths,
like maybe we won’t still be in denial after seeing another video of sensitive content
we can finally admit that this needs to end...until we forget. again.
until the next time another name made hashtag,
another body splashes across a friend’s insta story
a reminder that the death toll is never paused,
continually in counting,
yet lacking constant coverage,
it’s a brutal cycle running on replay, but hey, life goes on
until the next shot.

and yet it still takes a bloodbath before we can even recognise this racial hate,
why is there a required red quota for social change?
you cannot measure a struggle by the blood or the suffering or hate
that you see if so much goes unseen, so many wait
silenced by the raging roar of the united states,
but only a body bag will make it to the front page.
never the poster boy, never plaster the face of a boy both black and alive

the news headlines
are more often “black boy shot”
than “scholar”.
why are there more places for these kids in the prison system and graveyards than in college graduations?

why does it take another death for us to start paying attention?
why is breaking news always another broken family?
why do we still have to mourn those who were killed by the culture of a country who taught from crib to coffin to treat them like second class citizens?
like black bodies are only worthy of the spotlight, in the casket, once all that’s left are the rotting white bones underneath.

Sign this petition to demand justice for George Floyd- https://www.change.org/p/mayor-jacob-frey-justice-for-george-floyd?utm_source=brand_us&utm_medium=media

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter & Music: Documenting Contemporary Culture
snippet.description:
A panel of ethnomusicologists and contributors to the book "Black Lives Matter and Music" looked towards the present state of the movement to discuss economic injustices, gentrification and cultural displacement, as well as education disparities as enduring kinds of violence. The 2018 scholarly volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" collected critical studies which draw from ethnographic research and personal encounters to illustrate how scholarly research and teaching about the role of music in the Black Lives Matter movement can contribute to public awareness of social, economic, political, scientific and other injustice in our society. Michael Brown was shot and killed by police in 2014, catapulting digital activism from social media hashtags to uprisings in the streets. #SayHerName, a protest of police violence against Black women, followed. Black Lives Matter as a movement has been ardently committed to revealing who people are, but it is also rooted in a concern with revealing how things work. Systematic inequality was the reason for Alicia Garza's rallying cry for #BlackLivesMatter in 2013 after the acquittal of the killer of the unarmed 17-year old Trayvon Martin. Panelists also discussed how musicians continue to provide the soundtrack for the Black Lives Matter movement. Presented with the support of the Daniel A.P. Murray Association.  

- Fernando Orejuela is a senior lecturer in folklore and ethnomusicology and adjunct professor of African American and African diaspora studies and Latino studies at Indiana University. He is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Stephanie Shonekan.

 - Folklorist and ethnomusicologist Stephanie Shonekan is a professor and the chair of the W.E.B. Du Bois Department of Afro-American Studies at University of Massachusetts, Amherst. She is a co-editor of the book "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection" with Fernando Orejuela. 

- Alison Martin is a contributor to the volume "Black Lives Matter and Music: Protest, Intervention, Reflection." 

For transcript and more information, visit https://www.loc.gov/item/webcast-9189

snippet.title: ‘Black Lives Matter Is a Joke’ — Black D.C. Resident Tells Far-Left Group ‘Go to Chicago’
snippet.description: “I don’t want our country to be portrayed like this,” said an African-now-American citizen, pointing to a group of George Floyd protesters in downtown Washington, DC, Sunday. Nestride Yumga, a D.C. resident, was told to shut up and leave when she voiced her opinion that Black Lives Matter protesters are “hypocrites.” “When black people kill black people, they don’t come out and do this crap.”

snippet.title: George Floyd, Black Lives Matter from Civil Rights Movement Tribute | Marvin Gaye’s Flyin High
snippet.description:
Former officer Derek Chauvin of the Minneapolis Police Department is charged with third-degree murder and manslaughter for the death of George Floyd.  #ripandjusticeforgeorgefloyd #georgefloyd #civilrights #blackpanther #icantbreathe

I wasn't able to go out, march and support all the brothas and sistas at this moment out in our communities so I thought I would make a tribute to assist with awareness.  Marvin Gaye spoke to me when I was younger and still does to this day it just takes on a whole new meaning.

The struggle continues.  Thank you all of the amazing photographers that captured unfortunate events in our community, black and national history.

snippet.title: In Solidarity. Black Lives Matter.
snippet.description:
#blackouttuesday

“One could not be a calm, cool, and detached scientist while Negroes were lynched, murdered, and starved” - W.E.B. Du Bois

1)  Letter for Black Lives (a set of crowdsourced, multilingual, and culturally-aware resources aimed at creating a space for open and honest conversations about racial justice, police violence, and anti-Blackness in our families and communities): https://lettersforblacklives.com/

2) ResistBot: https://resist.bot/

3) CampaignZero: https://www.joincampaignzero.org/
BailFunds: https://bailfunds.github.io/?fbclid=IwAR1uYiuaLMrVQ4QGX3Zi06iwWGdumrPatRGKsv9HQoQrmJSptSI1-aE_vfk
Other Places to Donate: 
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/u/1/d/1p7QxOvtvRfHUoMWib8coGHSS8szENXzSjIZKpvp-gtA/htmlview?fbclid=IwAR2e_Fo1QjJK9c4X9TMvSNuxGebq-AR7sVa5WGiYdCn9A9Wb2qy6-RUgfl8

4) Anti-Racist resources & information
https://www.npr.org/2016/02/16/466942135/remembering-anarcha-lucy-and-betsey-the-mothers-of-modern-gynecology
https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/tuskegee-study-medical-distrust-research/487439/
https://www.npr.org/2011/03/18/134622044/tracing-the-immortal-cells-of-henrietta-lacks
https://journals.lww.com/academicmedicine/Abstract/9000/Changing_How_Race_Is_Portrayed_in_Medical.97189.aspx
https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/29/books/review/antiracist-reading-list-ibram-x-kendi.html
https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1BRlF2_zhNe86SGgHa6-VlBO-QgirITwCTugSfKie5Fs/mobilebasic
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tL9_huJWJ_iekHzK5PShI00u-C25w0jrExhpJpuNHII/edit
https://revealnews.org/episodes/reproducing-racism/

Note: These are only a very small sampling of the many resources out there. We encourage you to seek out your own information and share it below.

A compilation of Black voices in medicine & science to follow on Twitter: https://twitter.com/thenocturnists/status/1267079297526673408

snippet.description:
Samba do Trovão 
Samba = Alegria 
Trovão = Ruído Forte 
Momentos não compreendidos. Limites, sem limite. Bravura intrépida, ignorância impoluta. 
Máquina para lavar a alma. Uma caneca para esquentar o coração. 
Instrumentos simples e necessários. 
Instrumentos utilizados: Máquina de lavar roupa e Caneca de Inox. 
#BlackLivesMatter #georgefloyd

snippet.title: BREATHLESS - Original song - BLACK LIVES MATTER
snippet.description:
‘Breathless’ is an original song against police brutality and racism.

VIOLENCE is not the solution.
SILENCE is an easy solution but it not help at all. So I decided to raise my voice my way.

DISCLAIMER : 
I'm not a native English-speaker. If there's any mistake about the English, I apologize for that. Please, no hate !!! 

I am aware that I will never know how does it feel to be oppressed because of my skin color. However I've got eyes to see all this pain and this disgusting brutality against black people in the world. I want to help, I want to stand by them.

BLACK LIVES MATTER
RACISM MUST STOP 
POLICE BRUTALITY MUST STOP

#blacklivesmatter

snippet.title: Police Officer takes a knee outside Downing Street at Black Lives Matter march in London
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

A police officer outside Downing Street was filmed taking the knee alongside protesters marching in solidarity with Black Lives Matter.

Thousands gathered in Hyde Park on Wednesday before marching on Parliament Square in response to the killing of George Floyd in the US.

Traffic was blocked in certain areas as some climbed on phone boxes and sculptures with megaphones to whip up loud chants of "silence is violence" and "say his name, George Floyd".​

Read more: https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-police-office-take-knee-downing-street-a4459081.html

snippet.title: Speak Up- Black Lives Matter! ✊🏾 | With Love Jenae'
snippet.description:
✊🏾 Black. Lives. Matter. ✊🏾
Our country is once again in an uproar over the senseless killing of black people. We are living in some crazy times and more and more we are seeing that people don't really value black lives. Black lives STILL matter. 

My opinions may be unpopular. But to premier my Youtube page without addressing the obvious would be irresponsible. This was an impromptu video but I said what I felt needed to be said about what is going on. 

My beautiful black kings and queens, keep fighting. Keep speaking up. Be wise and be safe in these crazy times. Educate yourselves on what you can do to help be part of the solution and not the problem. That goes for EVERYONE. And more than anything- PRAY, PRAY, PRAY!!! Despite the chaos, God is able. And I'm holding on to that. You should too.

I've tagged some petitions at the bottom of this description. PLEASE if you can sign them and donate if you have the means to! Every little bit helps.


✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾BLACK LIVES MATTER. TODAY. EVERYDAY. AND ALWAYS.✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾✊🏾

Thank you so much for checking out my video! Be sure to like, comment, subscribe, and turn on those alerts because I'm coming back with bangers! 💥💥💥💥💥

snippet.title: Seoul 'Black Lives Matter' protesters rally for end to racial discrimination
snippet.description:
미국 조지 플로이드 시위, 한국 시민들도 동참해

Protests continue in the U.S., now more peacefully, against the death of George Floyd at the hands of police.
The protests have spread worldwide, too, including here in Seoul this weekend.
Our Choi Won-jong was there.
The protesters on Saturday, many of them wearing black shirts, held signs in both Korean and English, calling for an end to racism.
More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

#Seoul #Black_Lives_Matter #racialdiscrimination

📣 Arirang News(Twitter) : https://twitter.com/arirangtvnews

More than 100 people have gathered here in Seoul to show their solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement, and they are marching with one message - social justice.
"To support Black Lives Matter... because we are sick and tired of all the racism that goes on against. Especially, me as a black person, we are just sick and tired of what's going on."
The protestors were chanting phrases like Black Lives Matter and I Can't Breathe.
And though police were on the scene, they were able to make their voices heard without any interference.
The protesters are far from the state of Minnesota, where George Floyd was killed, but they say their movement is global.
"I mean at the end of your day racism is not a problem that's exclusive, and isolate to United States. I think it's a problem in humanity. It's something that needs to address globally."
"I hope we can build a world in which we can breathe. Even though we live in different countries, I think the world we want to live in is the same. We will work together and create a world free of discrimination."
In Korea, more than one-hundred 20 organizations signed a joint statement last Friday paying tribute to George Floyd and criticizing police brutality.
The government, however, has not yet made an official statement on them or the worldwide movement.
Choi Won-jong, Arirang News.

snippet.title: Thousands of Hawaii protesters rally for Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Support for the Black Lives Matter movement following the killing of George Floyd swelled in Honolulu Saturday as thousands marched peacefully from Ala Moana Beach Park to the state Capitol.

The march represents the state’s largest demonstration of a handful over the last week or so calling for justice for the black community. One organizer estimated about 5,000-10,000 people participated.

Video by Dennis Oda and Cassie Ordonio

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Co-Founder: Protests Are the Result of "Police Terror with No Accountability"
snippet.description:
As thousands in Los Angeles continue to protest against police brutality and face mass arrests, Mayor Eric Garcetti is facing criticism for increasing the budget for the Los Angeles Police Department. Organizers have called on the City Council to enact a People's Budget that slashes money for police and invests in services for the community instead. "We have created a system that overrelies on law enforcement and prioritizes their money, their budget, their needs over everything else," says Patrisse Cullors, co-founder of Black Lives Matter, and Reform L.A. Jails. "Now is the time that we redirect resources back into our communities."

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Short Film - 2020
snippet.description:
We all have a responsibility to do something.  To make sure no one is treated unfairly because of race.  We're all human, wearing a different jacket but what separates the good from the evil is our compassion, understanding and love.

A riot is the language of the unheard.
Injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.
Darkness cannot drive out darkness; only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate; only love can do that.

snippet.title: Hypocrisy 'at the heart' of the Black Lives Matter movement
snippet.description:
The Black Lives Matter movement lost a lot of support when its leaders failed to condemn the widespread violence and looting conducted in the wake of George Floyd’s death, according to Turning Point USA’s Rob Smith.

Protesters took to the street at the end of last month after George Floyd’s death in custody in the US city of Minneapolis on May 25th.

The images of Mr Floyd pinned to the floor beneath the knee of police officer Derek Chauvin inspired protests across the country.

Mr Chauvin has subsequently been charged with second-degree murder and second-degree manslaughter.

Three other offices involved in Mr Floyd’s death have also been charged.

While many protested police brutality peacefully, there were also shocking examples of violence, particularly in Minneapolis where widespread looting, riots and arson took place.

Mr Smith told Sky News the response to Mr Floyd’s death show the “hypocrisy of what is going on” in Black Lives Matter movement.

“The vast majority of people that were affected by the devastated in Minneapolis, which by the way there is devastated in New York City, devastation in Atlanta, the people who are going to be living with the effects of this are African American,” he said.

To excuse some of the brutality we saw in those riots, to excuse the destruction, to excuse the amount of people who had their livelihoods absolutely destroyed in the names of Black Lives Matter… I don’t think it’s a good thing to excuse it.”

Where a lot of the leaders of that movement truly lost me, and I believe they lost a lot of people, is when they didn’t speak out against this destruction when this first started because it helped them further their agenda.”

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter  București
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter
Intervenție de solidaritate anti-rasistă

Stop abuzurilor, stop rasismului, stop fascismului!Ne exprimăm solidaritatea cu mișcarea Black Lives Matter și condamnăm violența poliției împotriva persoanelor de culoare!
Poliția ucide și brutalizează, iar noi nu mai putem rămâne pasivi în față rasismului și a discriminării! 
STOP abuzurilor de putere! 

Onorăm memoria celor uciși de Poliție și tragem un semnal de alarmă: această violență trebuie să se oprească acum! George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Arbery în Statele Unite, Pedro Matos Pinto în Brazilia sau Manuel Fernandez în Spania sunt doar câteva dintre numele celor care au fost uciși recent din motive bazate pe ura rasială. Culoarea pielii nu este o crimă! În timpul pandemiei Covid-19 abuzurile împotriva comunităților de culoare au crescut sub justificarea restricțiilor de izolare, dar nu există nicio justificare pentru crimă! 
Condamnăm supremația albă în toate formele sale: rasismul sistemic, crimele și violența poliției, patriarhatul, colorismul, capitalismul, clasismul, ura împotriva femeilor, persoanelor transgen și a lucratoarelor sexuale!

Pentru afro-americani, șansele de a fi uciși de poliție sunt de 2.5 ori mai mari decât pentru persoanele albe. Atragem atenția și asupra rasismului din România: persoanele de culoare sunt hărțuite pe stradă, poliția și jandarmeria au comis nenumărate acte de brutalitate împotriva romilor: în ultimii ani, 7 romi au fost omorâți de către poliție iar alți 187 au fost bătuți și torturați! În ultimele săptămâni, poliția a intrat cu forță în comunități de romi ca Bolintin Vale, Săcele, Rahova și au bătut inclusiv copii și femei. În toată Europa, rasismul, colorismul, puterea partidelor fasciste și neo-naziste sunt în creștere și pun în pericol viețile persoanelor de culoare și ale romilor!
Să nu uităm: capitalismul global se hrănește din muncă persoanelor de culoare care au fost supuse sclaviei și colonialismului iar eliberarea societăților noastre este posibilă doar când capitalismul global va înceta să le exploateze pe toate surorile și frații noștri de culoare. Pentru o eliberare și o libertate adevărată, trebuie să demontăm toate sistemele instituționale care susțin supremația albă. Trebuie să înălțăm vocile oamenilor de culoare, vocile femeilor, vocile persoanelor transgen! 

Vrem să trăim într-o lume în care persoanele de culoare nu sunt ucise de poliție și nu sunt subiectul abuzurilor poliției. Vrem să trăim într-o societate care își asumă responsabilitatea asupra secolelor de sclavie, linșărilor și a opresiunii sistemice împotriva persoanelor de culoare. 

Vrem să trăim într-o lume care luptă împotriva guvernelor și a sistemelor opresive care permit ca aceste crime să se întâmple! Vrem să trăim într-o societate care reflectă asupra rolului său în menținerea acestor sisteme de opresiune. O societate care recunoaște că este complice acestor crime atunci când alege să nu vorbească despre ele.

O societate care se responsabilizează în a promova educația anti-rasistă în școli și în instituțiile statului pentru a opri moștenirea transgenerationala a rasismului.
Vrem să trăim într-o societate care acționează, și nu stă deoparte când astfel de lucruri se întâmplă!

Doar în condițile acestea putem fi cu adevărat liberi și libere.
Suntem solidare și solidari cu comunitatea afro-americana! Luptele noastre comune împotriva supremației albe sunt legate, însă alianța noastră cu BLACK LIVES MATTER este dincolo de lupta noastră anti-rasistă!

#BlackLivesMatter
#SolidaritateInternațională
#RasismulNeSufocă
#PolițiaUcide
#antifascism
#antirasism
