snippet.title: LL Cool J and Kalparkr - Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd (Official Demo Audio)
snippet.description:
We believe that black lives matter! This is LL Cool J's and Kalparkr's Black Lives Matter tribute to George Floyd as well as every black person that has been killed, racially profiled or harassed! LL Cool J gave a powerful speech that completely embodies the hurt blacks are still going through all over the world. 

Below is  the summary of the George Floyd incident that lead to his death. 
 On May 25, 2020, George Floyd, an African-American man, died in the Powderhorn community of Minneapolis, Minnesota. 

While Floyd was handcuffed and lying face down on a city street during an arrest, Derek Chauvin, a white American Minneapolis police officer, kept his knee on the right side of Floyd's neck for 8 minutes and 46 seconds; according to the criminal complaint against Chauvin, 2 minutes and 53 seconds of that time occurred after Floyd became unresponsive. Officers Tou Thao, J. Alexander Kueng, and Thomas K. Lane participated in Floyd's arrest, with Kueng holding Floyd's back, Lane holding his legs, and Thao looking on and forcibly preventing intervention by onlookers as he stood nearby.

Sad😢 to see the harm that some police officers inflict based on suspicion. Let us all pray for them today that they'll be patient enough to resolve matters without first breaking wrists, body slamming, shooting or disgracing us. Let there be peace on earth! Don't be quiet!

George Floyd is not the only Black American male that has perished in such a hateful manner but the people are taking a stand against this injustice in 2020.

Lyrics for Chorus:

They want us to be , silent! But this time that's gonna be hard
We believe we got to build a defense where we can shelter from this war

We'll take this no longer, longer, longer, no!
Raise your fists say black lives matter
Together we are stronger, stronger, stronger, yeah!
Shout it again black lives matter!

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protests spread to streets of Australia
snippet.description:
Thousands of protesters have flouted social distancing restrictions by marching through the Sydney CBD in solidarity with demonstrators in the US over the death of George Floyd.

The 'Black Lives Matter' rally started in Hyde Park before making its way to State Parliament. 

Authorities said the protest remained entirely peaceful and no arrests were made. 

A second, larger rally is scheduled for the weekend.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter NYC protestors applaud healthcare working during march down 1st Ave June 2, 2020
snippet.description: On June 2, 2020, a very large Black Lives Matter protest, spurred on by the murder of George Floyd by police officers in Minneapolis, marched up 1st Ave on Manhattan’s Upper East Side. As the march passed the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer center the protesters applauded and thanked the healthcare workers who are currently working every day to battle Covid-19.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter | Am I Next?
snippet.description:
“Am I Next?” is an unfortunate powerful art story where we gathered our Black Deaf individuals in our community to share the heart of what we are feeling and experiencing.  ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It has been an emotional roller coaster of turmoil for the entire nation of us Black people. There is so much pain, injustice in the system and exhaustion. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Bringing this to light, we hope this will push the movement of change forward for absolute justice, action, unity, consciousness, and love in this country. At the end of all this, we want to dismantle systematic racism for good. We are counting on you to make that happen. ⁣⁣
⁣
Please free share and forward the video.⁣
⁣⁣
Written and Produced by ⁣⁣
Natasha Ofili & Storm Smith⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Creative Direction by ⁣⁣
Storm Smith ⁣⁣
⁣
THANK YOU for everyone in Black Deaf Community participated in this and made this beautiful piece happened. ⁣
⁣⁣
#AmINext #BlackLivesMatter #enoughisenough

----
Transcript and Video Description

Black background with white text

“If you are freely able to: sleep, ride a bike, go for a run, go to the gym, walk the dog, drive to school, work or a nice stroll, tuck your children in bed..

“Then YOU have no idea. Because we CAN’T do ANYTHING FREELY without FEAR. Here’s the most haunting question we have to ask ourselves. Everyday.”

In Black and White color tone
 
Side by side of Black female wearing a gray top and Black male wearing a white sweater with graphic tee top signing:
“Am I next?” 

A couple of a Black male wearing a gray top and Black pregnant female wearing a gray top signing:
“Am I next? Is our baby next?” 

A Black male wearing a black vest over a white top & ripped jeans signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black female wearing a gray top and Black male wearing a white pattern top with black long sleeves signing:
“Am I next?” 

A Black female wearing a white sweater signing:
“Am I next?” 

A Black female wearing a black top  signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male wearing a headband with graphic tank top and Black female swearing a light white v-neck sweater with necklace signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male tiny white headband with Gallaudet Bison Basketball graphic tee and Black female signing with black top with pattern bandana:
“Am I next?”

A Black male wearing hooded signing:
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black female wearing a glass with black top and Black male wearing a beanie hat and white sweater signing:
“Am I next?”

A Black male wearing a black top with chains signing:
“Am I next?”


A Black female wearing pattern-tone top signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side of Black male wearing a black turtle neck with glasses and Black female wearing a white top with glasses signing:
“Am I next?”

A Black female a hat with black sweater signing 
“Am I next?”

Side by side a Back Male wearing a gray hat with black top and a Black Male wearing a graphic tee top 


Side by side a Back Male wearing a gray top and a Black Male wearing a hat with black button down top  

Black man sitting down with a black top raises his hands 

Black background with white text: 

“We are in fear that our last breath will be sooner than that it should be.“

“Our last breath. This is our reality.”

Zoom in collage of black and white photos of Black Deaf people with black bar and white text in the center: 

“246 years of slavery 1619 - 1886”

“99 years of Jim Crow Laws 1865 - 1964”

“86 years of lynching 1882 - 1986” 

“14 years of Civil Rights Movement 1954 - 1968” 

“316 years of Police Brutality 1706 - ?”

Black background with white text:

"Black Lives matter. Our Lives Matter Everyday.”

“Written and Produced by Natasha Ofili & Storm Smith. Creative Direction by Storm Smith”

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER JUSTICE NO MATTER
snippet.description:
I wrote this poem the other day based on one of my favourite quotes. 
The system wasn’t made to serve everyone. The system fails a lot of people. I see that. I want to fight that. I want to change that. 
I have my words. I have my privilege. I urge everyone to use their white privilege for the better. To not loose momentum long after the Instagram stories stop. After the donations dwindle. I urge you to carry on the fight. To remember these feelings. To remember these cries. 
I urge you to never forget. 
There’s a protest here in Manchester on Saturday at 1pm. I’ll post on my stories about it. 
Let’s use our voices until we see the change we really need. 
The change our brothers and sisters need !!!! This is our problem too ! 
#blacklivesmatter 
@donte.colley @florencegiven @troubletongues

snippet.title: VLOG: Black Lives Matter & Waking up the collective consciousness
snippet.description:
This is the 2nd video 
As people started to speak up in outrage
Looking at my Timeline I felt like I was yelling at a wall
Whilst not wanting to go for people or make divisive statements
It was clear that we were all witnessing systemic injustice and oppression and some people chose to remain silent, or sent teary eyes but were not investing themselves in the situation or asking the important questions like

HOW DID THIS HAPPEN?

WHAT CAN I DO?

Well meaning smileys and crying faces just like you would to a cat video is not the appropriate reaction to a planned out murder and the type of police brutality you see in this video.

This video is also honouring the legacy of people of all races, who have not been offended by the blanket statement of "white priviledge" or the visceral words thrust at them by some hurt members of my community but have stood by us and are standing by us in this moment when we need the most.
Women like Juliette Hampton Morgan and Virginia Foster Durr & men like James Reeb and many more who must and will be recognised sacrificed a lot to stand with us - this is their duty as human beings and prisoners of conscience. But in this day and age many people will not even sacrifice one swift movement of their thumb to like or share or sign a petition which is the least one can do.

As a man I cant help but wish I could have 1 or 2 hours alone with the policeman who was punching that woman, watching these videos and immersing myself in their pain was very distressing, so im grateful to all who chose not to look away

snippet.title: Thousands in London protest to say 'Black Lives Matter'
snippet.description:

The crowds chanted "I can't breathe" -- a reference to the death of George Floyd, in Minneapolis, who was killed when a policeman knelt on his neck.

Sky's Home Affairs editor Jason Farrell reports from London.

snippet.title: Wheres Black Lives Matter Now? Tophertownmusic Talks About Captain David Dorn.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest I  President Ramaphosa says George Floyd's murder has opened deep wounds
snippet.description:
President Cyril Ramaphosa says the killing of George Floyd has opened deep wounds for the country. He has described his killing as a brutal reminder of what South Africa once experienced. 
President Ramaphosa made the comments while delivering a birthday message to former Rivonia Trialist Andrew Mlangeni.

For more news, visit sabcnews.com and also #SABCNews, #Coronavirus, #COVID19 on Social Media.

snippet.title: Glasgow says Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The murder of George Floyd has brought worldwide attention to the systemic, anti-black racism that continues to exist in America and beyond. This includes in our own city, Glasgow, which has not yet confronted the legacy of its slave trading past.

In the 1700s Glasgow grew rapidly, becoming the ‘second city of Empire’, thanks largely to its role in the cotton, sugar and tobacco trades. The city’s merchants controlled much of the global trade in these commodities, owning plantations in America and the West Indies where tens of thousands of slaves toiled for their Glaswegian masters.

Many of Glasgow’s most famous streets were built off the back of slave labour, and named after the city’s celebrated ‘tobacco lords’.

We have now added alternative names to some of these streets to mark the legacy of slavery – celebrating those who rebelled against it and who fought for its abolition, and for civil rights and liberation. We also remember those who continue to bear the brunt of bias and police brutality, three centuries on.

Joseph Knight was taken from Africa to a sugar plantation in Jamaica owned by a wealthy Scottish landowner who later brought him back to Scotland. Knight escaped and fought against his former master in court, ensuring that slavery was illegal in Scotland.

Harriet Tubman was born into slavery in the American state of Maryland before escaping at the age of 27. She helped set hundreds more free, including when leading a daring raid on a plantation fighting for the anti-slavery side in the American Civil War.

Rosa Parks was another brilliant woman who struck one of the first blows for equal rights in America. From Montgomery, Alabama, Parks by law had to sit at the back of public buses and give up her seat to any white passengers who needed one. On the first day of December, 1955 she refused to do so, sparking the eventually successful campaign for civil rights in America.

Fred Hampton was born in Chicago in 1948. In his short life, he united the street gangs of Chicago against their common enemy – the racist state – and his leadership skills saw him rise through the ranks of the Black Panthers, a revolutionary organisation which fed the poor and challenged police brutality in black communities. Aged just 21, he was assassinated by the FBI.

Despite the advances won by Joseph Knight, Harriet Tubman, Rosa Parks, Fred Hampton and many others, black people continue to suffer from discrimination and to die at the hands of the state, here in Scotland, in America and elsewhere. 

In 2015, Sheku Bayoh, a 32 year old father from Kircaldy in Fife, was murdered by nine officers from Police Scotland, who used batons, CS gas and leg restraints on him. Sheku suffered 23 separate injuries and died from suffocation as police officers kneeled and lay on him for several minutes. He couldn’t breathe. The cops refused to talk for more than a month until they’d got their stories straight. No-one has ever faced justice for Sheku’s death, and his killers continue to walk the streets of Scotland.

Five years later, George Floyd died in very similar circumstances in Minnesota. Unlike the case of Sheku Bayoh, the cops involved now face the full weight of the law, which they had themselves applied on the neck of their helpless victim. 

George Floyd’s death provoked public outrage and has prompted many of us to examine our consciences, and our consciousness. We must now ask whether Glasgow should continue to celebrate the names of the city’s slave masters instead of icons of the fight against slavery and for equal rights, and why we are not demanding justice for Sheku Bayoh and George Floyd and an end to bias and police brutality. Where Glasgow once led the world’s slave-reliant industries, it must now lead in tackling racism.

snippet.title: Peaceful Black Lives Matter Protesters Get Creative | NowThis
snippet.description:
» Subscribe to NowThis: http://go.nowth.is/News_Subscribe
» Sign up for our newsletter KnowThis to get the biggest stories of the day delivered straight to your inbox: https://go.nowth.is/KnowThis

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 

From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

snippet.title: Small Black Lives Matter protest in Tel Aviv
snippet.description:
(2 Jun 2020) Hundreds of people protested outside a US diplomatic office in Tel Aviv on Tuesday to decry the killing of George Floyd.
The protesters held signs reading "Black Lives Matter" and carried placards bearng Floyd's name.
Floyd, a 46-year-old man, died in Minneapolis last week after a police officer pressed his knee into his neck for several minutes even after he stopped moving and pleading for air.
Some protesters wrote the name of Solomon Teka, an 18-year-old Ethiopian Israeli, shot last year by an off-duty officer who claims he and his family felt threatened from a group of rioting teenagers while at a playground in the city of Haifa, northern Israel.
Ethiopian Israelis complain of racism, lack of opportunity, endemic poverty and routine police harassment.
Ethiopian Jews began arriving in large numbers in the 1970s and many were airlifted to Israel in clandestine operations in the 1980s and '90s during periods of unrest. 
The community is now estimated at approximately 150,000, or around two percent of the country's population.

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" by Fanta Ballo
snippet.description:
BLACKLIVESMATTER, We will not be silenced. Spoken Word Poetry 

“Say Our Names, Remember Our Faces” , I have been sitting on this poem for a while because every time I read it I get angry and feel like I cant give the poem justice. The truth is our black bodies have been dying at the hands of corrupt police officers. We don't even know the names of some of these people because their stories don't make it mainstream. As I was making this video I see that there are way more people who die at the hands of police than we even know. After the heinous killing of Ahmaud Aubrey, I feel like this had to be posted. Sadly Ahmaud Aubrey won't be the last Black person killed at the hands of White Supremacy, there needs to be change but let's not ever forget our fallen soldiers.

Welcome to my channel !! Here I will post my original poetry videos. Please give it a listen and let me know what you think. 

Let me know your favorite line ! Open to all feedback. 

Road to 1k. 

#BLM #Blacklivematter #StopKillingUs

Sub Count: 287
Goal: 500 !!

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/fantaratty

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest   May 31st, 2020
snippet.description: This was the peaceful protest held in Eugene, OR on May 31st, 2020 in honor of George Floyd. The parallels between the happenings of present day and the words of Martin Luther King Jr. back in 1963 are uncanny. So, I added excerpts of the famous "I Have a Dream" speech into that footage in hopes that others might see the parallels, as well.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter! By YmX
snippet.description:
Recent events have taken a toll on me and I'd normally keep quiet for the fear of being misunderstood or not saying the right words but I'm learning that I have a responsibility to use my voice in the face of injustice and nothing will be achieved through silence! 

So here I am, using my 'voice' and this is only the beginning...

We are in this together and we need to support each other and continue to use our voices or anything we have, and one day, when the glory comes...It will be ours! 

#BlackLivesMatter #StopTheInjustice

snippet.title: Dwayne Johnson’s Black Lives Matter Speech Calls for Compassionate Leader
snippet.description:
Dwayne Johnson is looking for a unifying leader. The actor took to social media and delivered a sobering message directly to the camera, showing his support for Black Lives Matter and while he never mentions Trump by name, his frustration with the sitting leadership is made clear by his criticism. "Where is our compassionate leader who’s going to step up to our country who’s down on its knees, and extend a hand and say, ‘You stand up, stand up with me because I got you, I hear you, I’m listening to you,' Johnson stated.

snippet.title: How to Support BLACK LIVES MATTER as a South Asian #shorts
snippet.description:
This is how you can help supporting the Black community as a fellow South Asian.

First of all acknowledge there is anti-black sentiments in our South Asian community. No need to get defensive, we know the truth hurts. Once we have acknowledged this issue we can start addressing it by educating our friends and family. Don’t be afraid of calling people out. Doesn’t matter if it’s your parents or family friends or your coworkers. Then make sure you get your priorities straight during elections. People matter more than your economy because there is no economy without people. But the elites will brainwash you into thinking different. Also seriously y’all need to STOP SAYING ALL LIVES MATTER. WE KNOW THAT. The whole point of BLM was that BLACK LIVES MATTER TOO. We will not undermine the struggles of the Black community in order to avoid discussions that make you feel uncomfortable. #blacklivesmatter #shorts #pushpeksidhu

snippet.title: Do Black Lives Matter in Medicine?
snippet.description:
Board certified ObGyn discusses race, healthcare disparities, racism, and medicine. What are the social and societal constructs of race and institutional racism that affect health and access to healthcare in the United States?

RESOURCES:
- ACOG Committee Opinion: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx
- Health Coverage for POC: http://kff.org/disparities-policy/fact-sheet/health-coverage-for-the-black-population-today-and-under-the-affordable-care-act
- Sterilized in the name of public health: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx#O10-57-2
- Patient-physician social concordance, medical visit communication & perception: https://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/Fulltext/2015/12000/Committee_Opinion_No__649__Racial_and_Ethnic.57.aspx#O12-57-2

snippet.title: DISKUSI: #BLACKLIVESMATTER DAN PAPUA
snippet.description:
Senin (25/5) lalu, George Floyd (46), seorang warga Amerika berkulit hitam lehernya diinjak menggunakan dengkul oleh anggota Polisi AS berkulit putih, hingga membuatnya kehabisan nafas dan tewas. Kejadian tersebut dipicuh saat Floyd diduga melakukan tindakan pidana penipuan dan pemalsuan ketika berbelanja di sebuah toko di kota Minnepolis.

Kejadian tersebut terekam dan tersebar cepat di sosial media hingga mengundang protes besar-besaran. Kejadian ini juga menjadi topik hangat di sosial media di seluruh dunia, ditandai dengan penggunaan tagar #BlackLivesMatter. Gaungnya juga sampai ke Indonesia. Orang Indonesia turut mengecam tindakan kepolisian AS tersebut dengan turut menyuarakan tagar serupa. 

Jika ingin jujur, Indonesia juga bukannya bersih dari kasus diskriminasi rasial terhadap orang berkulit hitam. Orang Papua sebagai representasi dari orang kulit hitam kerap mendapatkan diskriminasi, terutama dilakukan oleh aparat keamanan Indonesia. 

Kejadian hampir serupa dengan yang dialami George Floyd juga pernah terjadi di Indonesia, tepatnya di Yogyakarta. Saat itu pada bulan Juli 2016, asrama mahasiswa Papua dikepung oleh aparat dan ormas selama hampir 2 hari.

Salah seorang mahasiswa bernama Obby Kogoya yang hendak masuk memberikan bantuan makanan ke dalam asrama dihadang, dituduh membawa senjata tajam dan hendak ditangkap. Obby yang berupaya melarikan diri dikejar, dan dijatuhkan ke tanah sembari diinjak. Dia kemudian dikenakan tuduhan melawan petugas. 

Masih segar dalam ingatan kita ketika Asrama Papua di Surabaya dikepung oleh aparat keamanan beserta ormas pada Agustus 2019 lalu. Pengepungan disertai dengan tindakan diskriminasi rasial dengan teriakan "Monyet" Kepada penghuni asrama. Kejadian ini memicu protes besar-besaran tidak hanya di Papua. 

Lantas bisakah kampanye #BlackLivesMatter juga disematkan pada orang Papua?

Following the recent events, I choose to break the silence to pay a tribute to George Floyd, afro-american man killed by the police, with an Indie-Pop styled composition of my own. Those racist crimes happen as well in the US than everywhere else in the world (even here in France) and that is why we're all involved and must stood up against it.

snippet.title: "Black Lives Matter" es un chiste, denuncia una mujer negra valiente
snippet.description:
"Los racistas son ustedes" ... sin palabras, tienen que ver este discurso de esta mujer valiente. Por más personas como ella en el mundo.

Nota sobre la oradora: Su nombre es Nestride Yumga. Ella nació y creció en Camerún. Más tarde se mudaría a los Estados Unidos para unirse a su familia. Ella se aplicó en la escuela y obtuvo una Maestría en Administración de Salud y también membresía en la Sociedad Nacional de Honor. Además, ha sido sido una activa modelo de fashion, trabajando para clientes como Covergirl, Macy’s, Kohl’s, Clinque y muchos más.

Ella vino como inmigrante de un país africano, y porque trabajó duro y no se victimizó, tuvo éxito. Mientras tanto, en todo Estados Unidos, muchos han nacido y han sido criados aquí, pero porque han sido alimentados con ideologías victimarias progresistas, al tener las mismas oportunidades desde el momento en que nacen, se convierten en matones, vagabundos, vándalos y completamente dependientes del gobierno.

No, no hay "problema racial" en Estados Unidos, lo que sí hay es un mensaje ideológico, impulsado por la izquierda política, que debilita las mentes, las morales y el espíritu de esta joven generación que se traga cualquier cuento para excusar su propia irresponsabilidad.

➡️➡️➡️ Para más vídeos, síganme en Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/ConservadorCristiano/

➡️➡️➡️ Para más vídeos, síganme en Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/ConservadorCristiano/

snippet.title: George Floyd Memorial Workout | Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Say his name.

George Floyd.

Today we're going to remember Floyd and bring awareness to the racism that persists in our government and police systems.

When this memorial workout starts to become difficult, know that it doesn't scratch the surface of suffering countless Black Americans face on a daily basis.

"George Floyd"
9 Min. AMRAP (as many reps as possible)
5 Bar Facing Burpees + 1 Clean and Jerk (155lbs/135lbs)
10 Bar Facing Burpees + 2 Clean and Jerk
15 Bar Facing Burpees + 3 Clean and Jerk
Etc.
Wear a 20lbs weight vest throughout.

Some reasoning behind the design of the workout: 9 minutes is the amount of time an officer weighing roughly 155lbs knelt on the back of his neck, over $20, until Floyd suffocated.

Over and over again he said "I can't breathe" just like Eric Garner did in 2014. 6 years later and nothings changed. At one point he was crying out for his mother while he died from a man kneeling on him with his hands cuffed from behind his back.

When are we going to learn? This is what I know so this is where I'm starting.

I hope you'll join me in this workout but further more, I hope you start with what you know.

Check those around you who perpetuate racism, donate to the NAACP, Color of Change, and other organizations for the Black Lives Matters movement, research your city's police code and find if they're mandated to wear body cam, etc. 

If you're wanting to help with the black lives matter movement, below is a link to donate to the NAACAP Legal Defense Fund.

https://org2.salsalabs.com/o/6857/p/salsa/donation/common/public/?donate_page_KEY=16304&track=DUXXX1G&utm_source=2020searchgoogle&utm_medium=search&utm_campaign=searchevergreen&gclid=Cj0KCQjw_ez2BRCyARIsAJfg-ksdh060dvMuJ9jZczErthwDavom6a7YUiwH8htd02nKI12-SvHUWooaAsjFEALw_wcB

This workout was originally made by my man Peter, owner of WakandaFit LLC. Follow him and his business on IG and YouTube.

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY
snippet.description:
A PRAYER FOR ALL OUR BROTHERS AND SISTERS IN THIS TIME. 

Almighty Father,

Violence, anger and hate are running the streets that you have created. Satan has stolen, killed and destroyed what you have made for us. There is no peace in the land. There is no justice amongst your people. The sinful crimes of the enemy have made the hearts of your children heavy. Hear our cries heavenly King, see our pain O Righteous One and feel our hurt. 

Scripture says that “The Lord is a shelter for the oppressed, a refuge in times of trouble. Those who know your name trust in you, for you, O Lord, do not abandon those who search for you”, (Psalms 9:9-10). Let your children be reminded that in this season of pain, we must search for your grace to fall upon your people, so that you may restore peace and justice in the land.

Matthew 5:44 “But I say, love your enemies! Pray for those who persecute you!”

Father, we pray for those who persecute us and hate us, we declare a veil of protection over us all in this season. We pray that we may find refuge and security in your scriptures. We pray for the families that have lost loved ones to the unjust. We pray for our spirits to be filled with faith and strength so that we are able to cast away all works of satan. 

May your will and you will alone be done over the land. May your blessings be on your people. 

Psalms 46:10 “Be still, and know that I am God”

AMEN.

#BLACKLIVESMATTER #BLACKOUTTUESDAY

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protest in downtown Lee's Summit
snippet.description: A crowd of approximately 40 people gathered outside City Hall in downtown Lee's Summit, Mo on June 2, 2020 for a #BlackLivesMatter demonstration. Interviewed are co-organizer and Lee's Summit North senior Ella Larson, Lee's Summit resident Corey McDonald and Lee's Summit Mayor Bill Baird.

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter | They don't care about us.
snippet.description:
Hey guys, so I wanted to give a break on posting edits to say something really important. I think you all know about what's going on, and I really felt like I needed to do something to spread the message of the movement, so I did this video to show my support to #BlackLivesMatter, this video doesn't show half of the brutality that these people suffer every day but I really want to make you guys reflect about racism and everything wrong with out society. This song is very special too, and I put scenes of people I admire, like Viola Davis, movies/series that shows us that we need to fight for what is right, I really like the speech of Katniss on Mockingjay, the series "When They See us"is just incredible, and I love "The Hate U Give" too... I was not worried about HD scenes, or anything like that, I just knew I needed to do something to show my support! Hope you guys can use this video to reflect, share this with your friends and let's be on the right side :) 

Sincerely, Holy Wolf.

WAYS YOU CAN HELP! https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co

snippet.title: Coronavirus: 'Black lives matter’ BAME and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from COVID-19
snippet.description:
Black and ethnic minorities are more than twice as likely to die from Covid than white people, an alarming new report has found.

The shocking findings shows men of working class age are twice as likely to die than women, too.

Seperate analysis has found 64 per cent of NHS and social care workers who died were from a BAME background.

Ministers ordered the review after several studies suggested that those from BAME backgrounds were more likely to catch the bug.

And it also concluded that age, and even what job you do, could affect your chances of getting it too.

The review into the risk factors of dying from coronavirus said: "The largest disparity found was by age.

"Among people already diagnosed with COVID19, people who were 80 or older were seventy times more likely to die than those under 40.

"Risk of dying among those diagnosed with COVID-19 was also higher in males than females.

While speaking about the risk to BAME communities, Matt Hancock told MPs today that "black lives matter" - the catchphrase of the massive protests throughout the US and the world, sparked by the death of a black man, George Floyd at the hands of a white policeman. 

Read more
Black and ethnic minorities twice as likely to die from Covid than white people as Hancock says ‘black lives matter’

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Somali boxer Ramla Ali vows to give part of earnings to #BlackLivesMatter causes
snippet.description:
Ramla Ali intends to donate 25 per cent of her professional boxing earnings over her first year to charities associated to the #BlackLivesMatter movement.

The Somali boxer, signed to Anthony Joshua's management label, is making the gesture in solidarity with George Floyd, the African-American killed in police custody whose death has sparked protests in the US.

Ali's family fled war-torn Somalia as refugees after her brother had already been killed. Settling in London, she initially kept her boxing training a secret for fear her family would disapprove of the pastime for a Muslim girl.

snippet.title: Documentary: Why Black Lives Matter
snippet.description: After the killing of George Floyd by police officer Derek Chauvin by kneeling on the persons neck I look into wider instances of black history and the black lives matter movement. I look into the history of African Americans in the USA from the start as being slaves to the civil war and the fugitive slave act. I look into other black icons like Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr and how they managed to get rid of the black codes to bring about the civil rights movement. Finally I compare what has happened since to examine whether president Obama or Trump have really done enough to address the injustice that black Americans are more likely to face police brutality.

snippet.title: DC Mayor sends message to Trump with giant 'Black Lives Matter' sign outside White House
snippet.description:
Washington mayor Muriel Bowser on Friday renamed an area near the White House as "Black Lives Matter Plaza" and unveiled a giant painted road sign, in a pointed salvo to President Trump over the policing of DC.

The protests are focused on the May 25 death in Minneapolis of 46-year-old black man George Floyd while in police custody. A white officer kneeled on his neck until he lost consciousness.

Read more about the Black Lives Matter Plaza in front of the White House:
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/06/05/dc-mayor-sends-message-trump-giant-black-lives-matter-sign-outside/?WT.mc_id=tmg_youtube_offsite_televideo-youtubevideo&utm_source=tmgoff&utm_medium=tmg_youtube&utm_content=offsite_televideo&utm_campaign=tmg_youtube_offsite_televideo-youtubevideo

That officer and three others are now in custody and facing charges - second-degree murder for the kneeling officer, and aiding and abetting that crime for his colleagues.

Get the latest headlines: https://www.telegraph.co.uk/


Telegraph.co.uk and YouTube.com/TelegraphTV are websites of The Telegraph, the UK's best-selling quality daily newspaper providing news and analysis on UK and world events, business, sport, lifestyle and culture.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters stage marches around the world
snippet.description:
Protesters have taken to the streets across the world to show solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement.

The protests were sparked by the death in police custody of an unarmed African American man, George Floyd. He died after a white police officer was seen kneeling on his throat for eight minutes as he gasped for breath.

snippet.title: Los Angeles black lives matter protest killing of George Floyd
snippet.description: DOWNTOWN LA: On 05-27-20 at approximately 5pm, a couple hundred black lives matter protesters gathered in Downtown LA to protest police brutality. Anger has risen after the death of George Floyd. Protestors took over the freeway and intersections. Some protestors began hitting and getting on top of a CHP patrol car. The officer began to pull away as the crowds began surrounding the patrol car. A protestor on top of the patrol car fell off the patrol car. The protestor was injured and transported to a local hospital. A second CHP officer pulled up to the injured protestor and the crowd began surrounding that second patrol car. Protestors began kicking it and shattered the back window. That officer also pulled away for their own safety. The protestors then got off the freeway and began taking over city streets. Protestors damaged police cars, spray painted the police station and threw items at police officers. Protestors also lit up a US flag on fire. During the protest, some protesters took over an intersection trapping cars. A car tried to drive through the crowd and a protester began hitting the car not getting out of its way. The driver of the car sped up and struck the protestor. The protestor suffered minor injuries and declined medical attention. Arrests were made during the protest and no officers were injured.

snippet.title: These Hands of Change - Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
Do not support me. This is not to promote myself- it is to use what abilities I have to try to support something greater. 

Support the movement. Support and listen to the voices of black people. Support the peaceful protesters who are being harmed and jailed. Support the lives lost by making their losses meaningful. Support community. Support change. Support a better future. 

Educate yourself. Spread awareness. Sign petitions. Contact your local officials. Donate. Watch videos and streams whose revenue will be donated in your place. Big or small, you can help make a change. Below are only a few options. Please research and choose what you want with your own breath. 

_ Sign Amnesty International's message to Minnesota Governor Tim Walz urging a clear message against excessive force by law enforcement upon minority persons, concerning the murder of George Floyd: 
https://www.amnesty.org/en/get-involved/take-action/george-floyd-police-violence-usa/ 

_ Join ColorofChange in texting "Floyd" to 55156 urging Mayor Jacob Frey that the officers involved in the murder of George Floyd are barred from becoming police officers again and do not receive related pensions: https://www.facebook.com/colorofchange/photos/a.10150403486291067/10158122764106067/?type=3&theater 

_ Watch Zoe Amira's video series fundraiser for BLM associated protester bail funds, featuring the content of black artists: 
https://youtu.be/bCgLa25fDHM 

_ Fund non-profit independent journalism covering criminal justice: 
https://www.themarshallproject.org/donate 

_ Take care of your holistic health to protect yourself against becoming overwhelmed and prevent compassion fatigue, and forgive yourself for your limits. Every mark matters, even the little ones. Do what you can. 

And remember- Protesters are protesting, looters are looting. Do not confuse them. Do not allow the juxtaposition in media to contaminate the message.

snippet.title: "Not Enough" SuNWhoa Love #BlackLivesMatter
snippet.description:
With a heavy heart, I wrote this song for me. 

In light of the last 400+ years, this video is for us. Every time I close my eyes and think about the many black lives snatched away too soon, their unlawful murders flash before my minds eye. The killing of Ahmaud Arbery and George Floyd most recently. The shooting of Philando Castile and Tamir Rice before that. The lifeless bodies of Sandra Bland, Eric Garner & Freddie Gray. These are only a few that come to mind. These traumatizing images seem to be engraved in my memory. God put it on my heart to show a different image. I pray this black girl magic doesn't distract you from the message, but this black girl magic is the message. I'm still trying to completely understand what it means to me metaphorically, but I know we need these images too.

We are a beautiful, resilient, and innovative people. Forced to double dutch through a country that doesn't love us. When we peacefully protest, you say that's not enough. When we fight wars, win gold medals, and create cultural standards, you still say that's not enough. What contributions must we make for you to deem our lives valuable enough to let us breathe. 

"I had to learn that hitting back with my fists one individual was not enough. It takes organization. It takes dedication. It takes the willingness to stand by and do what has to be done, when it has to be done." - Ella Josephine Baker

Love Y'all!
Thank you! 

-SuNWhoa

Written & Produced By SuNWhoa Love
Mixed By Kevin Randolph
Featuring video clips from "Black Magic" a Documentary by David Hoffman

snippet.title: WHO'S GEORGE? BLACK LIVES MATTER(GEORGE FLOYD( من هو جورج ؟ مسألة الحياة السوداء (جورج فلويد) (مترجم
snippet.description:
BLACK LIVES MATTER

George Perry Floyd. (October 14, 1973 – May 25, 2020) was a 46-year-old African-American man who was born in Fayetteville, North Carolina, and raised in Houston, Texas. He attended Yates High School, where he played on the basketball and football teams. Floyd was a star tight end for Yates, helping them to the 1992 state championship final game. He attended South Florida Community College (now South Florida State College) from 1993 to 1995 and played on the school's basketball team. Floyd returned to Houston, where he joined the hip hop group Screwed Up Click and rapped under the stage name "Big Floyd", after entering the Houston Hip Hop cultural scene as an automotive customizer. In 2014, Floyd moved to Minnesota. He lived in St. Louis Park and worked in nearby Minneapolis as a restaurant security guard for five years, but lost his job due to Minnesota's stay-at-home order during the COVID-19 pandemic. Floyd was the father of two daughters, ages 6 and 22, who remained in Houston.

snippet.title: Paris police death rally backs Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
(2 Jun 2020) Thousands of people converged on a court building in Paris on Tuesday to show solidarity with U.S. protesters and to denounce the death of a black man in French police custody.
The demonstration was organized to honor Frenchman Adama Traore, who died shortly after his arrest in 2016, and in solidarity with Americans demonstrating against George Floyd's death in the U.S.  
The Traore case has become emblematic of the fight against police brutality in France. 
The circumstances of the death of Adama Traore, a French 24-year-old man of Malian origin, are still under investigation by justice authorities. 
French police claimed Traore died of a heart attack due to pre-existing medical condition.
His family said he died from asphyxiation due to police violence and has asked for the officers in charge of Traore's arrest to go on trial.
Protesters defied a police ban imposed a few hours before the demonstration, forbidding any gatherings of more than 10 people.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter to God & to Us
snippet.description: George Floyd's death has impacted our multicultural church in NYC so deeply that we dedicated this Sunday discussion to the topic. Tears have flowed throughout our congregation, and brokenness and fears have been communicated. We are asking the question: WHAT DOES GOD HAVE TO SAY ABOUT RACISM? Interestingly, the Bible has so much to say — words of hope and encouragement, as well as warnings against the dangers of haughtiness. Jump in and get plugged into this discussion. We're praying for healing of hearts, reconciliation, and unity. Black lives matter so much to God, and we want the world to know they matter to all of us as well.

snippet.title: How Name Shaming Impacts Health Outcomes: Conversation encouraged by Black Lives Matter and Protests
snippet.description:
This time in history has been an amazing learning opportunity for many people. More people have been learning and posting more about civil liberties injustices as well as health disparities that impact black communities. 

The COVID 19 pandemic has re-highlighted the reality of overall worse health outcomes for black people regardless of their SES. Physicians must realize their role in this issue. Often there are a sum of many small things that add up to discriminatory behavior. Not intentionally finding and working against unconscious bias is one of them.

snippet.title: Police horse bolts at Black Lives Matter protesters in London
snippet.description:
Mounted and riot police clashed with protesters on London's Whitehall on Saturday, during demonstrations being held in solidarity with similar protests worldwide after the death of George Floyd in the US.

Police officers on horses charged down Whitehall, before a police officer was dismounted after hitting a traffic light, causing one police horse to run free.

Afterwards, police in riot gear were filmed marching toward protesters.

snippet.title: I Can't Breathe: Cellist Performs Dido's Lament for Black Lives Matter Protest
snippet.description:
NYC Cellist Yves Dhar performs a five-cello arrangement of "When I am laid in earth" (Dido's Lament) from Henry Purcell's Dido and Aeneas as a protest for Black Lives Matter and artistic tribute to George Floyd.

#icantbreathe
#BlackLivesMatter
#GeorgeFloyd 
#taketwoknees
#handsupdontshoot
#EnoughIsEnough

Recorded and produced entirely sheltered-in-place near Clearwater, FL after leaving New York City temporarily for the Covid-19 pandemic.  As an artist and longtime advocate dedicated to using music to inspire, to educate, and to make the world a better place, Yves Dhar (@yvesdhar) joins his friends and colleagues in Anthony McGill's #taketwoknees, a call-to-action for musicians to fight police brutality and systemic racism.

YouTube video footage courtesy of @antoniofonsecx, Eric Thomas, CBSN, WPLG Local 10, Sacramento Bee.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: A Virtual Celebration of Black Theatre Artists
snippet.description:
Broadway Sessions will present a digital Black Lives Matter fundraising concert on June 4th. This celebration of Black Theatre Artists will feature Black performers sharing not only songs, but their thoughts  on anti racism, police brutality and how others may get involved to affect much needed change.  The concert will be live streamed on multiple platforms at 8:30pm EST. 

Artists scheduled to appear include Antoine L Smith (Ragtime, MJ the Musical), Warren Egypt Franklin (Hamilton), Ari Groover (Tina), Angela Birchett (The Color Purple, The Clark Sisters), Doulas Lyons (Beautiful, writer Polka Dots The Cool Kids Musical, Beau), Kyle Taylor Parker (Kinky Boots, Smokey Joe’s Cafe), DeMarius Copes (Dear Evan Hansen), Asmeret Ghebremichael (Legally Blonde, Dreamgirls), Brittney Mack (Six), Michael Demby Cain (Beauty and the Beast, Victor/Victoria), Laquet Sharnell (Memphis, The Lion King), Destan Owens (Rent), Joy Woods (Little Shop of Horrors),  Imari Hardon (Ave Q), singers Shavon Lloyd, Subiya Mboya and more.

Viewers are encouraged to donate to important organizations including Black Lives Matter, Black Visions Collective, Color of Change and more.

Broadway Sessions is committed to using it’s platform to promote and support Black artists and stands with the Black Lives Matter movement.

snippet.title: Justice for George Floyd | Black Lives Matter

Eight minutes and 46 seconds was the length of time a police officer pinned his knee to George Floyd’s neck, leaving him unable to breathe. Join us as we take this time to stand united with the Black community against racism and voice that these brutal attacks must end.

These racist and brutal attacks must end.
We can’t allow the call for justice to be ignored.
Stand up with Color Of Change and countless others.

snippet.title: Deputy involved shooting/ Black Lives Matter protest
snippet.description:
5/29/2020

An unarmed man was shot on Ave. K and 17th St. West in Lancaster, CA. The shooting took place around 7:48pm. A news release from the Sheriff's Information Bureau said:
“Deputies observed a suspect, male white adult, walking eastbound on the sidewalk. As deputies contacted the suspect they saw he had a firearm in his hand. An altercation with the suspect ensued and the suspect was taken to the ground, during which time a deputy-involved shooting occurred."
A replica firearm was found on scene.

Later, a Black Lives Matter protest took place and ended peacefully around 1:30am the following day.

http://theavtimes.com/2020/05/30/man-killed-in-deputy-involved-shooting-in-lancaster-demonstration-follows/

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MdP9inYPch0

Please like, share and subscribe for more independent, local news media!

snippet.title: The Fight Continues- Black Lives Matter!
snippet.description:
A Song Compilation about The Struggle for Black Rights throughout the 20th Century. This was made a few years ago as a project for school but while it is extremely amateurish I thought given the current political context it is important to highlight how long the struggle has equality gone on. This only highlights the struggle through music but of course the struggle has been going on since before slavery. No one is equal until everyone is equal. Black.Lives.Matter!

#BLM #Protest #Music #Equality

snippet.title: Harrison Black Lives Matter protest
snippet.description:
Protesters holds signs, raise their voices in chants and kneel in a moment of silence Thursday, June 4, 2020, during a Black Lives Matter protest on the downtown Harrison square. The protest took place for about an hour and remained entirely peaceful. A few men armed with assault rifles stood nearby, stating they had no desire to confront the protesters, but wanted to protect their city from rioting or looting if it should occur. A member of the Ku Klux Klan made a brief appearance in plain clothes. 

Go to nwaonline.com for more photos and story. 

NWA Democrat-Gazette/Ben Goff

snippet.title: #BlackLivesMatter…무장 경찰 마주한 '5살 아이' 입에선 "우리를 쏠 건가요?" / JTBC News
snippet.description:
1. 흑인 남성 조지 플로이드가 백인 경찰의 무릎에 짓눌려 숨진 지 열흘이 지났습니다. 미국을 넘어 전 세계가 분노하고 있지만, 미국 경찰이 목을 눌러 체포한 건, 사실 어제 오늘 일이 아닙니다. 플로이드 사건 전에도, 또 후에도 계속됐는데요.

2. 미국 시위 사태의 중대 분수령이 될 희생자 플로이드의 추모행사, 그 첫 번째 추모식이 사건이 일어난 미니애폴리스에서 열렸습니다. 추모객들은 정의를 위한 투쟁을 멈출 수 없다고 했고, 유족들은 그의 죽음을 헛되이 하지 않겠다고 다짐했습니다.

3. 이제 미국에선 어린 아이들까지도 흑인 남성 플로이드가 어쩌다 숨졌는지 다 알게 됐죠. 시위 현장에서 한 5살 흑인 아이가 백인 경찰에게 "우리를 쏠 건가요"라고 물었는데요. 어른들에게 큰 울림을 주고 있습니다.

snippet.title: BLACK Lives Matter🖤 | Reads for Times Like These
snippet.description:
George Floyd was only ONE of MANY African Americans who have lost their lives at the feet of police officials. Police officials that take an oath to keep lawful order and protect citizens from violence, yet are QUICK to fear for their lives when they’re in the presence of someone who is Black. They are QUICK to approach them aggressively and later say it was self-defense. 

Why? 

BECAUSE THE ISSUE IS AND ALWAYS HAS BEEN RACISM. WHITE SUPREMACY IS REAL. 

See, the ideology of racism and the practice of ethnic domination was constructed by the majority against the minority; therefore, IT IS the majority’s job to put an end to these beliefs/practices and break these sick and malicious chains. 

RACISM IS AMERICA’S BIGGEST ISSUE. I mean we’re supposedly in debt too but 🤷🏽‍♀️.......

If you are of other races and you have Black friends, if you appreciate Black culture, if you support TRUE AND PURE EQUALITY, if you call yourself an AMERICAN then this is YOUR problem as well! 

SPEAK the truth! Use hashtags! PROTECT one another and be strategic when protesting ✊🏽! READ!!!!! 

For a while, there’s been a fire. The smoke has filled the lungs while the flames have been hot and in the faces of so many people. 

This is the inferno. 

#BlackLivesMatter #ThisIsAmerica #booktube #blackbooktube

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter, A BLM song (Sugar Coated Shiii), George Floyd, Travon Martin,
snippet.description:
Demand an end to this police brutality of Black men. The politicians will have to figure out a way to put an end to this. One day won’t matter, doesn’t matter your race, doesn’t matter your political party, NO ONE buy from the corporations, the corporations will take notice. Rioting and burning down our neighborhoods is one strategy. But, consider "this" one. Only buy locally! Store owners, put out a sign saying “Locally Owned Business.” We will patronize you!

Can we as a country spur our own economic growth? Can we stop falling for "Sugar Coated Shiii?"

This is just my idea. If you like it please share!

I welcome your thoughts.

Derek K. Cason

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER RIOTS: Looting at mall and surrounding businesses
snippet.description: A riot broke out at the Champaign Marketplace Mall. Macy's was broke into at first, leading to police and SWAT officers to defend the storefront. The crowd was full of protesters and anti-protesters. The violent acts continued later into the evening on May 31st. The city later put a curfew in place to help bring the flow of traffic to a minimum.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter "...But Not Enough For Me To Post About It On Instagram" | BiancaReneeToday
snippet.description:
Today's video is very different from my normal beauty content... but due to the current state of the world I felt like it was my responsibility as a black content creator to use my platform to try to make a positive change in the world.

Today I wanted to address all of you that have yet to post anything about the racial injustice and protesting that is happening right now. I asked all of you on Instagram why you haven't said anything and got many interesting response... this video is my response to your responses.

*NOTE* I did not get to touch on every reason I was sent but please understand this video is mainly directed to the people that have nothing to lose by posting on social media. OBVIOUSLY if posting will put you in danger, will get you disowned/ kicked out of the house by your parents, or will harm your mental health in any way, please continue to do your part privately. 

If you are able to donate on this video, the money will be donated to the NAACP. Please check out their website to learn more. http://www.naacp.org Even if you can only donate $1, YOU can make a difference!

In ADDITION to this YouTube fundraiser, I will also be donating all of the money generated from monitored ads on this video to the following organizations. So if you'd like to help donate, DO NOT SKIP THE ADS ON THIS VIDEO!
Black Lives Matter Global Network
National Bail Out
Know Your Rights Camp
Black Voters Matter Fund
Black Youth Project (BYP100)
NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund
The National Police Accountability Project
Color of Change Education Fund
Unicorn Riot
Campaign Zero
Advancement Project
The Marshall Project

I will be using this website that allows you to donate to all of the above organizations at once and will split the amounts equally. (I will update you all on how much is raised here and on Instagram @MzBiancaRenee )
https://secure.actblue.com/donate/ab_mn

For more information on Organizations and Petitions that are made to help achieve racial justice, check out these Google Docs my husband Royce created. (Thank you @RoroBeckley)

snippet.title: Driver ‘ploughs into George Floyd protester' at Black Lives Matter rally in Colorado
snippet.description:
A Driver was filmed speeding into George Floyd protestors in Denver on a third night of fury across America.

The driver of a vehicle ran over a protester during a George Floyd demonstration in Denver, Colorado.

Shocking video captured in Colorado appears to show a black Jeep Grand Cherokee plough into a group of protesters at a Black Lives Matter protest.

Protesters were rallying against the police-involved killing of black man George Floyd, in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

Footage from the Denver rally shows a driver speeding through a crowd of demonstrators before turning the car around and crashing into one of the protesters.

Protests, some violent, occurred across America since May 26, the day after video circulated of Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin pinning Floyd, 46, to the ground with his knee on his neck. Floyd died soon after, according to police.

Read more

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter
snippet.description:
The StudyTube Project stands with the black community and will continue to use all of our platform for the greater good. 
We will continue to help spread awareness and do so in a way that doesn’t take the focus away from the #BlackLivesMatter movement. 

Here are a few resources you can look through to educate yourselves on the matter and be actively anti-racist:

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter -  New Music and Video by Echoed Sycamore
snippet.description:
As an artist, I get most of my inspiration by daily events. After seeing recent events and tragedy that happened to George Floyd, I was not going to be able to stay silent so I have decided to express myself with the best way I can, through my music. These people have had enough! We need to do everything we can to put an end to racism. These reoccurring acts of racism are entirely unacceptable and are just cruel. Reacting to people practicing their rights should not be faced with violence, rather than listening and understanding so they can finally be heard. 

I am just an amateur when it comes to making videos. Most of the footage, I found from various documentaries and news channels from archives, and I edited them alongside of my original music. 

I hope this video serves a purpose. Maybe it gives new perspective and understanding for those who can not let hate and racism go. 

Video and Music by Echoed Sycamore/ Fatih B. Omeroglu

snippet.title: Black lives matter Demonstration in Fulda am 06.06.2020
snippet.description:
Nach dem gewaltsamen Tod des U.S. Bürgers George Floyd durch Polizeibeamte seiner Heimatstadt Minneapolis am 25.05.2020 gibt es seit Ende Mai, insbesondere in den Vereinigten Staaten von Amerika, aber auch weltweit Proteste gegen Rassismus und Polizeigewalt. Auch in Fulda haben am 06.06.2020 unter dem Motto der Black Lives Matter - Bewegung mehr als 2000 Menschen gegen Rassismus und rassistische Gewalt protestiert und damit ihre Solidarität mit den Demonstranten weltweit zum Ausdruck gebracht und auf das leider ebenfalls weltweite Problem Rassismus aufmerksam gemacht.
Die Demonstranten skandierten neben "black lives matter" auch "no justice, no peace" und "Stoppt den Rassismus" und zogen zunächst vom Universitätsplatz zum Platz Unterm Heilig Kreuz vor der Stadtpfarrkirche und später zum Bahnhofsplatz Fulda. Hier einige Impressionen.

snippet.title: #1 REASON WHY BLACK LIVES MATTER (MY STORY ON BEING RACIALLY  PROFILED BY THE POLICE)
snippet.description: The black community is hurting and we are all fed up by the injustice we experience daily. The murder of George Floyd and many others due to the effects of systemic racism constantly affects our mental wellbeing. We are tired of begging America to treat us as humans! We need solidarity and we need to share our individual experiences of racial profiling, police brutality, and the murdering of unarmed people of color at the hands of those sworn and paid to protect us.

snippet.title: Dre Fine$$e feat  Brock - BLM ( Black Lives Matter)
snippet.description:
#BlackLivesMatter was founded in 2013 in response to the acquittal of Trayvon Martin’s murderer. Black Lives Matter Foundation, Inc is a global organization in the US, UK, and Canada, whose mission is to eradicate white supremacy and build local power to intervene in violence inflicted on Black communities by the state and vigilantes. By combating and countering acts of violence, creating space for Black imagination and innovation, and centering Black joy, we are winning immediate improvements in our lives

Join the Movement to fight for Freedom, Liberation and Justice!

Video shows Floyd handcuffed with his neck pinned to the ground by an officer for over six minutes, gasping for air and saying “I can’t breath,” before he ultimately loses consciousness.

snippet.description:
ผู้ชุมนุมออกมาประท้วงในเมืองต่าง ๆ ทั่วสหรัฐอเมริกาติดต่อกันเป็นเวลาหนึ่งสัปดาห์ เพื่อประท้วงการเสียชีวิตของ จอร์จ ฟลอยด์ ชายแอฟริกันอเมริกันวัย 46 ปี ระหว่างที่เขาถูกตำรวจจับกุมตัวในเมืองมินนีแอโปลิส รัฐมินนิโซตาในวันที่ 25 พฤษภาคม

ผู้สื่อข่าววีโอเอได้พูดคุยกับผู้ชุมนุมบางส่วนที่มาประท้วงหน้าทำเนียบขาว ว่าอะไรเป็นสาเหตุให้พวกเขาเข้าร่วมการเคลื่อนไหวครั้งนี้

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe
snippet.description:
Black Lives Matter - Minneapolis - george floyd türkçe


#BlackLivesMatter. Sign a petition. Make a donation. Get informed. Make a phone call. Do it all here: https://ellen.tv/2Azjfwb

In US news and current events today, the Black Lives Matter protests have continued to boil over in over 140 cities across the US. Most stories you see are of riots, looting, and police brutality, but the George Floyd protests have been predominantly peaceful, and these Black Lives Matter protesters have come up with creative ways to have their voices heard in a peaceful manner. 


From the Cupid Shuffle dance to taking a knee in powerful moments of silence, peaceful protesters are simply trying to make a difference in the world and fight for racial justice, equality, and against police brutality. The BLM protests have opened the eyes of the world to injustice, and as the unrest continues, we should focus on the vast majority of peaceful protestors instead of the few bad actors trying to turn a beautiful movement into a riot.

Played by Arshia Jahanpour:
YOUTUBE: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC4an...
INSTAGRAM : https://www.instagram.com/arshiajahan...

snippet.title: BLACK LIVES MATTER
snippet.description:
USE YOUR VOICE:

Text “FLOYD” to 55156
Text “JUSTICE” to 668366

Sign this petition to re-open Darrien Hunt’s case. He was a cosplayer who was shot by the police 6 times: http://chng.it/BTtKYbXZB4

Send an email to the Las Vegas Mayor asking to repeal the Emergency Ordinance Bill No. E-2020-1 as it goes against the 1st Amendment’s rights. This bill prevents Las Vegas citizens from carrying essential things such as large purses, coolers, backpacks, fanny packs, cinch bags, camera bags, and even strollers during protests. Not only does it provide an inconvenience for the protestors but it also inconveniences on-sight medics. Please fill this form out, it’s quick and easy: https://cityoflasvegas.formstack.com/forms/contact_main 

Sign the “Hands-Up” act petition, which punishes police for shooting unarmed citizens: http://chng.it/kH67BznLjq 

Multiple pre-written emails to demand justice. It takes less than a few minutes to send MULTIPLE emails: https://emailforblm.com

Here is a link with a pre-written email to prosecute ALL of the police involved in George Floyd’s murder. All you have to do is fill out your name, city, and state: https://tinyurl.com/emailforfloyd

Here is a link with a pre-written email to prosecute the police involved in the death of Breonna Taylor. Again, fill out your name, city, and state: https://tinyurl.com/ycha6nuu

Multiple links to many petitions, ways to call/text, safe donation sites, & more: https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/

Another link with multiple ways to help: https://saytheirnames.carrd.co

If you don’t have any money to donate, watch this video to raise money for donations. 100% of the proceeds made on the video will be donated, your view can help: https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=bCgLa25fDHM&feature=youtu.be

Obama Foundation link with information on police violence & anti-racism. Educate yourself by clicking on this link: https://www.obama.org/anguish-and-action/

Help fund the Black Lives Matter movement: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/ms_blm_homepage_2019

Donate to the Vegas Freedom Fund to help bail arrested protestors: https://secure.actblue.com/donate/vegasfreedomfund
— Protestors in Las Vegas have been arrested with a bail raised to $1000. 

Sign this petition to ban rubber bullets: https://www.change.org/p/united-nations-ban-the-use-of-inhumane-rubber-bullets
— Rubber bullets are often metal encased in rubber. Although made to reduce momentum, rubber bullets can cause anything from fractures to even death. 

** I will be adding more reliable links to the description as I find them. I also post information on my other social media platforms (mainly Instagram & Twitter) @abbythejoy. You don’t have to follow, just click my stories (I usually have a lot of information reposted on there) and read anything I’ve posted regarding the BLM movement **

FEEL FREE to comment and/or DM me regarding any further information I can put on this video.



FILMS I HAVE PERSONALLY WATCHED TO EDUCATE MYSELF:

“When They See Us”
— A series that centers around the true story of the “Central Park 5”. Five boys (Korey Wise, Kevin Richardson, Raymond Santana, Antron Mcray & Yusef Salaam) were convicted of a crime they did not commit. Watching this series shows you the failed justice system.

“The Hate U Give”
— Similar to our situation today, The Hate U Give focuses on the injustice present in America. As some of you may not be able to endure the pain of the black community, watching this movie will help you understand the importance of using your voice and spreading awareness. This movie is based on a fiction book written by Angie Thomas, in reaction to the shooting of Oscar Grant.



As a minority, I understand the racism present within America and its justice systems. I understand my privileges and I choose to use them to stand with the black community. I understand the impact of my platform, and choose to share information to help more people become aware and further educate people on the matter. 
Please, use your voice. You don’t necessarily have to repost everything you see to your story, but spreading valuable information is important and definitely encouraged. Also, keep in mind that ONLY choosing to repost pictures is performative activism. It goes deeper than a repost, it’s signing petitions, donating, starting conversations, educating yourself, protesting, etc. Do what you can.

#BlackLivesMatter
#JusticeforGeorgeFloyd

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter protesters rally in London over killing of George Floyd - LIVE
snippet.description:
BLACK Lives Matter protesters filled central London streets over the death of George Floyd in the US.

People gather in Parliament Square, chanting 'No Justice No Peace' in the memory of George Floyd, a black man, who died after a white police officer knelt on his neck.

The 46-year-old was handcuffed and on the ground in Minneapolis earlier this week before falling unconscious.

Video of him pinned down, which has gone viral, shows Mr Floyd begging for air saying, "please, I can't breathe" and "don't kill me".

Protests have since flared up across the US, with the movement against police brutality going global.

On Saturday afternoon protesters in London carried placards reading "solidarity" and "Black lives matter".

Some read "the UK is not innocent" as dozens of people marched through Peckham, stopping buses and cars on the main road.

Read more
Black Lives Matter protesters block streets in London and promise more UK demos over death of George Floyd in US
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/11747570/black-lives-matter-london-protest-george-floyd/

snippet.title: Matt Hancock says 'black lives matter' after report shows BAME people hardest hit by coronavirus
snippet.description:
Subscribe to the Evening Standard on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7RQon_YwCnp_LbPtEwW65w?sub_confirmation=1

Matt Hancock has said “black lives matter” after an investigation found BAME people are the hardest hit by the pandemic.

The Health Secretary admitted “we need to do more” and said he felt “anger” over the racial injustice of coronavirus.

He said the Equalities Minister Kemi Badenoch would be looking into the report and that the Government was “absolutely determined” to find ways to close the gap.

He added: "There is much more work to be done and the report shows that."

Read more: https://cms.standard.co.uk/news/politics/matt-hancock-black-lives-matter-bame-report-coronavirus-a4457911.html

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter: Crowds in Rome Kneel For 8 Minutes to Honor George Floyd
snippet.description:
Several hundred people protested peacefully in Rome's Piazza del Popolo to denounce the killing of George Floyd and show solidarity with anti-racism protests in the U.S. and elsewhere.

In English and Italian, protesters chanted "I can't breathe!" and kneeled for 8 minutes and 46 seconds, the amount of time George Floyd was pinned under a white police officer’s knee before he died.

snippet.title: June, 1 2020 (Black Lives Matter) - Logan Kendell
snippet.description:
#blackouttuesday #blacklivesmatter #resist #isupporttheprotests #antifa
This is what my anger and anxiety sound like.
Further context for history sake:
Following the murder of George Floyd by Police officers, which came on the heels of the murders of Ahmaud Arbery and Breonna Taylor, also by police officers, Black Lives Matter Protesters took to the streets around the world to protest Police Brutality and systemic racism. Most protests started peacefully, some devolved into rioting and looting, and some were stirred to violence by the police and White Nationalist agitators.

On June 1st, 2020, after calling protesters "Terrorists" and blaming "Antifa" for violence (side note, it has now been revealed that white nationalists in support of Trump created fake Antifa accounts to provoke violence that would support the presidents lies) Donald Trump sent military police to attack the peaceful protesters who had gathered outside the White House. Protesters and the press were attacked with tear gas, rubber bullets, pepper bombs, and more, and they were physically beaten with bats by police. This was done so Trump could take a photo holding a bible in front of the church accross the street from the white house. Ironically, a church Trump had never attended, he held the bible upside down in the photo, and among those driven from the property by his stormtroopers were the leadership of the church itself who had set up a table to give aid to the protesters. The public joined together for "Black Out Tuesday" as a simple way to show support for the Black Lives Matter movement.
I composed this piece to underscore my rage towards the president, the alllivesmatter movement and all their racist supporters, the police, and the broken state of the USA.

snippet.title: Black Lives Matter Protest in Baldwin
snippet.description:
I’m so unbelievably proud to call Baldwin my hometown. The turnout for the BLM protest was more than I’d ever imagined, and it was beautiful to see so many people, regardless of color, care about a single marginalized group. I’ve never really thought about race, and that privilege was given to me by growing up in a diverse environment, and it’s a shame to see so much ignorance in people who weren’t as lucky. This beautiful poem was written by 15 year old Baldwin student, Jaylynn Valentin.

Jaylynn's Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/jaylynn_valentin/

snippet.title: Thousands attend Black Lives Matter protest at US embassy in Dublin
snippet.description:
Over 3,000 people held a Black Lives Matter demonstration outside the US embassy in Dublin today.

While they defied the advice of Chief Medical Officer Tony Holohan and Lord Mayor Brabazon to call off the protest on public health grounds, the majority of those who attended wore face masks.
